<HEAD>Rio Seeks Federal Aid to Avoid Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION> wants $ 54 million from the federal government to avoid bankruptcy, but federal officials said Tuesday that bailing out this celebrated tourist mecca would set a bad precedent. Presidential press spokesman <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Henrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> told reporters that if President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> helps <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION>, `` the next day there will be a line of 4,000 mayors knocking on the door of the presidential palace.'' Rio Mayor <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Saturnino </PERSON> <PERSON> Braga </PERSON> said last week that his city of 5 million people was broke and could not pay its debts or the salaries of 100,000 municipal employees unless <PERSON> Rio </PERSON> received federal aid. <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> is <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s second-largest city and a major tourist attraction. But Finance Minister <PERSON> Mailson </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Nobrega </PERSON> has refused the city's request to issue $ 54 million in emergency bonds. <PERSON> Rio </PERSON> has been hurt in the last few decades by the transfer of the federal capital to <LOCATION> Brasilia </LOCATION> and the flight of industry to <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paulo </LOCATION>, the nation's largest city. Today, <PERSON> Rio </PERSON> owes about $ 150 million to Brazilian creditors and another $ 150 million in foreign debts. The city has projected a budget deficit of close to $ 180 million this year. <PERSON> Saturnino </PERSON> <PERSON> Braga </PERSON> warned that the city may have to cut off school lunches and medical supplies to city hospitals unless its credit is extended. The mayor, a former economist who belongs to the fledgling Brazilian <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, also said the city was considering selling the <ORGANIZATION> Nelson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Piquet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Autodrome </ORGANIZATION>, named for its famous race car driver and the site of the annual Brazilian Formula 1 Grand Prix. He predicted financial chaos unless the city received aid. `` There could be a deterioration of the city. Chaos. General strikes, deterioration of public services and the conservation of the city. But we'll do everything possible to avoid bankruptcy'' he said in an interview over the weekend with the Jornal do Brasil newspaper of <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
