<HEAD>Sandinista-Contra Talks Begin in Guatemala</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with talks breaking off; PICKS
up 9th graf pvs: The agreement...
^By ALFONSO ANZUETO LOPEZ</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Representatives of the Nicaraguan government and rebel leaders met for the first time in three months Monday but broke off talks after failing to agree on a new location for resuming peace negotiations. The rebel delegation rejected the government's demand that future talks to end the 7-year-old civil war take place in the Nicaraguan capital of <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>, rebel leader <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferrey </PERSON> said after the meeting. The rebels proposed <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> or the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> as alternative sites for high-level negotiations, <PERSON> Ferrey </PERSON> said. Monday's meeting had been called as a preliminary step to resuming the peace talks that collapsed June 9. The four-hour session was the first meeting between the leftist government and the U.S.-backed rebels since talks collapsed. A possible second day of talks on Tuesday was ruled out, and no date for another meeting was announced. <PERSON> Ferrey </PERSON> said rebels were open to considering new proposals on a location for the talks, and the government has said it would keep trying to persuade the rebels to bargain in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ferrey </PERSON> said he reiterated a rebel proposal that high-level talks be held Sept. 26-28, but not in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. The proposal was contained in a letter he submitted to Nicaraguan Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON>, head of the government delegation, and was made available to reporters. The rebels, known as Contras, also demanded the government release more than 40 opposition demonstrators arrested in July and guarantee freedom of expression as a precondition to further talks. <PERSON> Ferrey </PERSON> said that during previous talks in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>, rebel leaders `` felt like prisoners in their own country'' and added, `` our telephone conversations were listened to.'' He did not elaborate. In a separate press conference, <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> said the government was sticking by its position that the talks be held in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. A fragile March 21 cease-fire remains in effect in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, but each side accuses the other of violating the truce. <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> had said before the meeting Monday he expected it to result in `` a cease-fire for 30 or 60 days that could be extended indefinitely.'' There was no announcement on extending the cease-fire. Both sides had agreed on March 23 to seek a negotiated settlement to the conflict the government says has claimed the lives of 28,000 Nicaraguans. <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> said Monday that that agreement called for <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> as the site of peace negotiations. The agreement called on the rebels to lay down their arms in exchange for democratic reforms. Shortly before peace talks broke off in June, the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> proposed a timetable for disarmament and political reforms. But the Contras rejected the plan, saying it did not go far enough. They demanded freedom for political prisoners and democratic reforms in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> before disarming. <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> will urge that a cease-fire verification commission funded by $ 10 million from congress be put into operation. Commission members would include the secretary-general of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Joao </PERSON> <PERSON> Baena </PERSON> <PERSON> Soares </PERSON>, and Nicaraguan Cardinal <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y Bravo. <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> also reiterated the government's demand that the Contras free 66 prisoners of war being held in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. He blamed the Contras for ending peace talks on June 9. `` The Contras broke them off to seek military aid in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. Direct <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid to the rebels ended Feb. 29, and the Contras have few bargaining chips left. Non-lethal <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to the Contras is distributed only in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. During the past four months, most of the rebel forces fled back to base camps inside <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> to receive new supplies of uniforms and food. Contra sources say only 2,000 fighters remain inside <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> while more than 9,000 are holed up in isolated camps in eastern <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. The cease-fire pact in March caused deep divisions within the rebel ranks. Militant Contras, led by <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON>, a former colonel under the deposed <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON> dictatorship, said the agreement was tantamount to surrender.
</TEXT>
