<BYLINE>Bill Kennedy</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT SMITH, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, a Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist and former <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Record </ORGANIZATION> editor, died Friday from complications of a heart attack. He was 64. As a reporter for the <LOCATION> Watsonville </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> -RRB- Register-Pajaronian, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> was named co-winner of the 1955 Pulitzer Prize for public service for exposing corruption in government. His coverage of that story brought him one of his two <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Big Story Award awards The stories were made into television dramas. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> was editor of the <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Record </ORGANIZATION> between 1971 and 1975 after heading the national news bureau of the <ORGANIZATION> Donrey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> D.C </ORGANIZATION>. Between 1975 and 1977, he was editor of the Donrey newspaper in <LOCATION> Hilo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>.
