<HEAD>Iraqi Foreign Minister Says Shatt Must Remain Iraqi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The crucial <PERSON> Shatt </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Arab </PERSON> waterway must remain under Iraqi control and can not be used by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> as a negotiating tool in peace talks to end their 8-year-old war, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s foreign minister was quoted as saying Monday Foreign Minister <PERSON> Tariq </PERSON> <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON> said the waterway, the delta of the <LOCATION> Tigris </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Euphrates </LOCATION> rivers and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s sole outlet to the sea, should remain under Iraqi control as `` a historical, logical, legal and a just matter,'' according to the official <ORGANIZATION> Iraqi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON>, speaking at a press conference, said <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> rejects what he said was <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s use of the waterway as a means to pressure <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in the U.N.-mediated peace talks that started in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> on Aug. 25, the agency reported. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> is demanding sovereignty over the <LOCATION> Shatt-al-Arab </LOCATION> estuary and that the outlet be cleared of sunken ships and silt. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s first wants to negotiate the withdrawal of both side's troops to internationally recognized borders, the exchange of war prisoners and a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> investigation to determine who started the war. The talks broke off Sept. 13 and are scheduled to resume in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in the first week of October. <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON> said that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> is committed to peace and that `` <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> would bear the consequences for its insistence on its current position.'' After the press conference, <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON> left <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> Riyadh </LOCATION> and consultations with King Fahd of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> about the negotiations and other `` issues of common interest,'' the news agency said. In a related development, the agency reported that President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> met with his military field commanders Monday and one item on the agenda was the possibility of changing the course of the Shatt <PERSON> al-Arab </PERSON>. Press reports in the region have said <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> is considering the project to change the path of the waterway in case its talks with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> deadlock completely.
