<HEAD>SAT Sample Questions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 How hard are SAT questions? Here are questions from a test administered on May 2, 1987, reprinted by permission of the <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Testing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, which is the copyright owner of the questions. Included is the percentage of test-takers correctly answering each. MATH: `` If a, b, and c are integers, the expression a -LRB- b + c -RRB- is always equal to each of the following EXCEPT -LRB- A -RRB- -LRB- a + b -RRB- c -LRB- B -RRB- a -LRB- c + b -RRB- -LRB- C -RRB- -LRB- c + b -RRB- a -LRB- D -RRB- ab + ac
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Answer is -LRB- A -RRB-; correctly answered by 79 percent of test-takers. `` If the average -LRB- arithmetic mean -RRB- of six numbers is -6, and the sum of four of the numbers is 20, what is the average of the other two numbers? -LRB- A -RRB- 7 -LRB- B -RRB- 8 -LRB- C -RRB- -8 -LRB- D -RRB- -28 -LRB- E -RRB- -32
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Answer is -LRB- D -RRB-; correctly answered by 16 percent of test-takers. VERBAL: Directions: Choose the word most nearly the OPPOSITE in meaning to the words in capital letters. `` UNCORK'' -LRB- A -RRB- reform -LRB- B -RRB- empty -LRB- C -RRB- seal -LRB- D -RRB- dry out -LRB- E -RRB- blend in
</TEXT>
