<SECOND>PM-Chile-Farm Politics,0791</SECOND>
<HEAD>In Chilean Farm Country, Political Question Is Tinged by Fear</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FERNANDO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the country's agricultural heartland, old ingrained fears tinge the debate over the referendum next month on Gen. <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s presidency. For prosperous landowners, frightening memories of farm seizures by leftist peasants in the early 1970s has helped push them solidly into the pro-Pinochet camp. `` This is the fear we have, of returning to the past,'' said <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Olea </PERSON>, owner of a 100-acre spread here in the country's fertile <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> But for struggling farm workers, the prospect of reprisal by their bosses or local officials is keeping many from openly voicing dissent. Some say resentment with <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s authoritarian rule, and with a hand-to-mouth existence, will find expression in the ballot box. `` At least before there was work, and the worker had the right to express his opinion,'' said laborer <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON>, as he painted a tractor by the roadside. Two farmhands with him made similar comments, but refused to give their names. Chileans will decide Oct. 5 in a yes or no ballot on a new term for <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, the right-wing army commander who seized power in a bloody 1973 coup and has already ruled longer than any previous president. If a majority vote for him, he will remain as president until 1997, but the military junta that he has headed as the governing body since 1973 will be disbanded. If he loses, open elections will be held in a year and he must hand over power in 1990, when a new <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, two-thirds elected and one-third appointed, will go into place. <PERSON> Farmowner </PERSON> <PERSON> Olea </PERSON> and others like him have benefited from an export-oriented, free-market economic program carried out by <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s administration. Foreign sales of grapes and other fruit, much of it grown in the <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, have been booming. With government credits and technological assistance, many farm owners are expanding production and making solid profits. But they have not forgotten the chaotic, radical reform programs launched by President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>, a self-declared Marxist elected in 1970 and toppled in the coup led by <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> three years later. <PERSON> Olea </PERSON>'s home and land were illegally seized by peasants. He negotiated with them so he could live in his house, which also had been taken over, while they worked his land as they liked. `` We lived through a savage lack of order,'' said <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Aullet </PERSON>, who is partner with his brother <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> in a 70-acre farm. `` There was no respect for your home, your land.'' <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> <PERSON> Aullet </PERSON> said the Allende government sent `` experts'' with no knowledge of agriculture to supervise land reform programs. `` What we fear is -LRB- that kind of -RRB- ignorance,'' he said. The landowners said that, with the production boom, conditions for farm workers were improving significantly. `` Manpower is becoming scarce, and there's competition in salaries to attract workers,'' <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> <PERSON> Aullet </PERSON> said. `` Anyone who wants work can find it.'' The Aullets said that at the height of the harvesting season, workers could not be found for less than 1,000 pesos, about twice the minimum legal daily wage and equivalent to about $ 4. Their positive vision of rural <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> is shared by <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s campaign strategists, who predict overwhelming voter support from the heartland Opposition leaders contend that the countryside's poor majority are suffering economically and are eager for a change but wo n't say so publicly because they fear losing their jobs or government benefits, such as pensions and housing subsidies. The opposition's political campaign is aimed at overcoming such fears, while recognizing them as legitimate. One prominent campaign slogan in the countryside is `` Say yes, but vote no.'' Several farm workers said harvesting jobs paid an average 700 pesos, or less than $ 3 a day, and lasted only a few months a year. `` You ca n't live on that,'' <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON>, who sells bread from the back of his small, battered truck in the countryside around <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fernando </LOCATION>, said most of his customers opposed <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s continued rule. `` I travel 50 kilometers -LRB- 30 miles -RRB- a day, and I can tell you there are a lot more people for the ` no' vote than the ` yes' vote,'' he said But he added: `` Lots of people may vote ` yes' because they're afraid. He said that in one remote town on his bread route, <LOCATION> Tinguiririca </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alto </LOCATION>, `` people are telling each other that if you vote ` no,' you'll be arrested.'' The government has said the vote will be secret, and the opposition has publicized its plans to have representatives at each polling place to prevent intimidation.
