<TEXT>
 American <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Louganis </PERSON> won his second consecutive Olympic gold medal in men's springboard diving Tuesday just a day after he hit the back of his head on the board. Sporting a bare spot on his head, <PERSON> Louganis </PERSON> gave a picturesque performance and knocked off two Chinese challengers. He finished with 730.80. Tan Liangde of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, runner-up to <PERSON> Louganis </PERSON> at the 1984 Summer Games, had 704.88 to win the silver medal and <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Deliang </PERSON> of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> finished with 665.28 to take the bronze. The other American, <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradshaw </PERSON>, came in fifth with 652.99, behind <PERSON> Albin </PERSON> <PERSON> Killat </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> who had 661.47 points. The dive that marred <PERSON> Louganis </PERSON>' performance in Monday's preliminaries caused him no problem Tuesday The reverse 2 -LCB- - somersault in the pike position earned three 9s, three 8.5 s and one In the preliminaries, he received two zeros, one .5, three 1s, one 1.5 and five stitches. <PERSON> Louganis </PERSON>, 28, is seeking to become the first man to win both the springboard and platform events in consecutive Olympics. He captured his first Olympic medal in 1976 when, at the age of 16, he finished second in the platform competition.
