<HEAD>Trip Serves to Prepare South Africa Voyage</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS REDMONT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>'s 10-day swing through <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has paradoxically served to reduce the stigma of any future visit to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, while firmly including the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> as a player in efforts to solve the region's conflicts. An unexpected touchdown in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, involvement in a hostage drama in <LOCATION> Lesotho </LOCATION>, and quiet diplomacy to nudge <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> away from confrontation marked a trip which initially had only the trappings of the fourth papal pastoral visit to the continent. `` You could say it was an act of grace,'' commented <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> Agostino </PERSON> <PERSON> Casaroli </PERSON>, pondering the consequences after bad weather forced a landing in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, the very country whose racial policies the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> excoriated at his first touchdown in <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>. Before <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>'s visit to <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lesotho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, some bishops and African leaders urged him to strike the nation of apartheid from any future travel, but by the time the pope landed in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> Monday night, few voices against a future stopover had been raised. Even the Rev. <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesak </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> anti-apartheid leader who attended a papal ecumenical papal meeting in <LOCATION> Maputo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, stopped short of discouraging a trip, despite his charges that the pope had been too soft on the white minority government. <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> prelates confirmed the pope would fly to <LOCATION> Madagascar </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tanzania </LOCATION> in 1989, and that he was considering a visit to rigidly Marxist <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. A customary Vatican procedure is to include countries of the same region on one trip, making the prospect of a <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> trip in the near future a distinct possibility. After all, the pope had now landed at Jan Smuts airport, sipped tea with Foreign Minister <PERSON> Pik </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, ridden 190 miles in a bulletproof government sedan, stopped for refreshments at an Afrikaner gas station and visited people injured in the storming in <LOCATION> Lesotho </LOCATION> of a hijacked bus, during which six people were killed by South African commandos. The pope, who has rarely held back from sensitive subjects on his foreign tours, continued to speak out: _ He lectured the 20-year-old king of <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION> and his four wives about polygamy _ He repeatedly nudged <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>'s Marxist government, overwhelmed by 6 million people on the edge of famine and by the ravages of a civil war, to sit down at the negotiating table with rebels, offering the church's help if needed The latter subject was all the more delicate since President <PERSON> Joaquim </PERSON> <PERSON> Chissano </PERSON>'s government until recently held on to confiscated church property, while the <ORGANIZATION> Mozambique </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> _ a shadowy group holding much of the country _ tried to depict itself to the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> and the outside world as anti-communist, and thus in favor of religious freedom. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> set his own agenda in some of the most graphic speeches of any papal trip, exclaming: `` Yes, my beloved brothers, I have felt the heart of this country bleed ... I am taking home images of suffering ... the worried gaze of many children, the look of uncertainty of so many youths, the tired eyes of so many adults and the sad look of the aged.'' Becoming unusually specific, he has permitted Mozambican bishops to encourage negotiations between the government and rebels, while backing a government program of amnesty which has already convinced 2,000 rebels to lay down their weapons. `` The pope's trip was like rain on scorched earth,'' commented <PERSON> Nampula </PERSON> <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> <PERSON> Dom </PERSON> <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Vieira </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinto </PERSON>, saying it marked a turning point in church-state relations. On the government side, <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Cabaco </PERSON>, head of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> FRELIMO </ORGANIZATION> party's foreign relations department, said <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> could endorse practically everything the pope had recommended. <PERSON> Cabaco </PERSON> added that the government also felt encouraged by the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>'s efforts to revive a non-aggression pact and economic cooperation with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and by the <PERSON> pope </PERSON>'s worldwide appeal for aid. According to diplomats, who spoke on condition of anonymity, the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> _ as it has done in the case of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and other countries _ is dangling the prospect of formal diplomatic relations with <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> as an incentive for it to continue supporting the regional peace process and the thaw in religious freedom.
