<HEAD>Rebel-Ordered Transport Ban Largely Heeded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A vast majority of bus and truck drivers heeded a nationwide transportation ban called by leftist rebels despite assurances from the military that traffic would be protected. Only a handful of mass transit buses circulated Monday in this capital of 1 million inhabitants, forcing workers to walk to their jobs or pay inflated fares to pickup truck and van owners. More than 70 percent of urban bus traffic was halted and inter-city service was even more severely curtailed, an official of the bus owners' association told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. A dispatcher at one of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s two terminals said 90 percent of the bus service between provinces was stopped. The indefinite ban on bus and truck traffic was the fifth called this year by Marxist-led guerrillas waging a nearly 9-year-old war against the U.S.-backed government. Previous rebel bans lasted three days each. The government urged citizens to ignore Monday's ban, saying the military would protect vehicles. Col. <PERSON> Mauricio </PERSON> <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON>, the army chief of operations, told <ORGANIZATION> YSU </ORGANIZATION> radio that about 13,000 soldiers were providing and protecting transport. `` We refuse to allow a violent minority to impose its will on us,'' he said. Soldiers rode shotgun aboard several state-owned buses circulating in the capital and some army trucks carried passengers to and from the city outskirts. <PERSON> Lorgio </PERSON> <PERSON> DeLeon </PERSON>, a 48-year-old father of six, was stranded at the eastern bus terminal with no way to get to his tailor's job in <LOCATION> Zacatecoluca </LOCATION>, 35 miles southeast of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. `` This hurts the poor worker more than anyone. We do n't work today, we get our pay docked,'' he said. Rebels of the <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> said the ban was in response to the actions of riot troops who broke up a Sept. 13 demonstration by leftist university students. The troops used tear gas and clubs and fired shots in the air to disperse nearly 3,000 students at that protest. About 250 demonstrators were arrested. All but 14 were subsequently released, with the remainder charged with what the government called `` terrorist acts.''
