<HEAD>Sketches Drawn From the Aftermath of Hurricane Gilbert</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some notes gathered in the aftermath of Hurricane Gilbert, which struck <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> on Sept. 12:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The 17 members of a <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> crew got caught up in the hurricane at <LOCATION> Kingston </LOCATION>'s Pegasus Hotel. The morning after, they took over the duties of hotel staffers, most of whom were unable to get to work. In return for free meals, flight attendants and cockpit crew waited tables, washed dishes, tended bar and lugged suitcases up to guests' rooms for a full day. For burser <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, the toughest part was washing dishes, pots and pans `` piled to the ceiling'' with no hot water. The answer was to use a little lime juice.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Power failure knocked out traffic lights in <LOCATION> Kingston </LOCATION>, and driving in the city of 750,000 inhabitants became a risky business. You nose into the road and hope oncoming cars stop and let you in. If they do n't, you just wait. At one especially busy intersection, a fellow wearing a bright red shirt and flowered bermuda shorts directed traffic with the flair of a seasoned cop.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 An insurance company's billboard that greets visitors to the northern coast resort of <PERSON> Ocho </PERSON> <PERSON> Rios </PERSON> could cause a shrug. The sign, a quarter of which was ripped away, carries the message: `` ` S YOUR HOME INSURED? If so, relax and enjoy the scenery.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Along with winds reaching 145 mph, Hurricane <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> dumped up to 10 inches of rain on <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, swelling rivers and reservoirs. But a week after the storm, water was in dangerously short supply because electricity had not been restored to most pumping and filtration stations. In <LOCATION> Kingston </LOCATION>, people gathered at burst water mains and open hydrants. In the countryside, roads were lined with people trudging behind wooden carts loaded with jugs and buckets filled with water. Women balanced plastic containers on their heads. Health officials warned against taking water from rivers and streams that could be contaminated by the carcasses of animals. Millions of water-purification tablets were being airlifted into the country.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Twelve families were sheltering at <LOCATION> Woodbourne </LOCATION> Seventh-day Adventist Church in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Thomas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Parish </LOCATION>, one of the four eastern Jamaican districts hardest hit by the hurricane. They told how the winds demolished their homes and furniture and and wiped out their meager farms. A slightly built teen-age boy was asked if he had anything to say. `` I feel frightened, sir,'' he said. `` We do n't have anyplace to live. It seemed cruel to ask him anything else.
</TEXT>
