<HEAD>Tighter Controls Needed on Dairy Promotion Program, Audit Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A national dairy promotion program financed by dairy farmers should be tightened to eliminate slipshod accounting methods, waste and unauthorized use of funds, an Agriculture Department audit says. The report by the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s office of inspector general criticized the <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, which administers the program, for not providing adequate guidelines and controls over those sharing in the funds, and for submitting incomplete information to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` AMS' annual report to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> did not include information relating to approximately 60 percent of the activities of the program,'' the auditors said. `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had not been informed as to the accountability of approximately $ 374.4 million of $ 619.7 million of the Dairy Promotion Program assessments for the three-year period ending April 30, 1987.'' The inspector general's office said it was looking into at least one case of possible fraud. However, it declined to provide details and said only that a report on the investigation would be issued later. The program was created by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in a 1983 law that imposes a mandatory assessment of 15 cents for each 100 pounds of milk produced and marketed in the 48 contiguous states. Producers may assign up to 10 cents of the assessment to regional or state qualified programs, or QPs, that have similar promotional projects. But at least 5 cents of the assessment must be sent to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dairy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Promotion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dairy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, which consists of 36 dairy farmers appointed by the secretary of agriculture. The board finances national promotional programs, including television commercials, to help sell more milk and other dairy products, all subject to review by AMS officials. According to the report, which has been circulating recently within the dairy industry and the department, auditors looked into the use of program funds during the period of May 1985 through May 1987 and `` other periods as deemed necessary.'' During that period, approximately 291 billion pounds of milk were marketed, with an assessment of around $ 436.9 million, of which almost $ 168.2 million was remitted to the national board and $ 268.7 million credited to the QPs. The audit report said: _ Five of the 18 QPs reviewed passed $ 14.7 million of $ 15.6 million in assessment funds collected to other QPs and incurred approximately $ 235,000 in administrative costs _ Two other QPs improperly used $ 106,500 for activities such as school activity funds, athletic tournaments, support of veterinary services, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Future </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> and other miscellaneous accounts _ Five QPs with assessments funds totaling about $ 20.5 million had internal control weaknesses such as separation of duties, management of promotional materials and procurement systems _ Four QPs incurred $ 2.4 million in administrative costs in excess of the 5 percent limit set by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dairy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> `` In the absence of guidelines concerning the use of the assessment funds, the QPs and an affiliated organization, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dairy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- of <LOCATION> Rosemont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION> -RRB-, had only their discretion to follow,'' the report said. Auditors said they questioned the association's classification of `` about $ 5.8 million of administrative costs as program costs, $ 1,500 in monthly per diem to the <ORGANIZATION> UDIA </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman of the board of directors and $ 85 per diem per day in excess of travel-related expenses to members of the <ORGANIZATION> UDIA </ORGANIZATION> board.'' The report recommended a general tightening up of procedures, including accounting by the QPs on how the money is spent. Also, the department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> should `` devise and implement guidelines'' that organizations must follow before getting any funds. In its comments, the AMS agreed to some of the audit report's recommendation but said its authority on others was limited and that action by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> may be required `` If the department concludes that such additional oversight is desirable, AMS would be willing to discuss'' with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> the purpose and legislative intent of the law authorizing the dairy promotion program, the marketing service said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When it comes to curbing the cotton boll weevil, it's a matter of timing and tillage rather than how much pesticide is used, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says. A seven-year study in the lower <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> led to a new state law last year that requires farmers to destroy cotton stalks by Sept. 15. By shredding the stalks and then following up with deep plowing, the destructive weevils are deprived of winter shelter and food when they are dormant. Entomologist <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Summy </PERSON> of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> says in a report that the <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION> study showed that farmers applied pesticides 15 times to 18 times a year in 1980 and 1981. But in 1984, following a year of `` moderate'' stalk destruction, chemicals only had to be applied three or four times, he said. From 1985 to 1987, pesticide use rose again, sometimes equaling 1981 levels, because farmers did n't destroy the cotton stalks. Last year the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> legislature passed the law requiring cotton growers to destroy stalks annually by Sept. 15 in the <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION> zone, later in other parts of the state. To help state officials enforce stalk destruction, <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> scientists worked out a surveillance system for cotton fields by using infrared aerial photos to detect which fields are not plowed by the deadline, <PERSON> Summy </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s 65th annual outlook conference has been scheduled for Nov. 29 through Dec. 1. Analysts from government and the private sector participate in the annual meetings to talk about the national and global economies, agriculture and trade in the coming year. Sessions will include forecasts for major farm commodities, including wheat, corn, soybeans, cotton and meat. Other meetings will focus on food prices, water quality, conservation aquaculture and transportation.
</TEXT>
