<HEAD>Census Planning Special Homeless Count</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A special effort to count the nation's homeless will be conducted as part of the 1990 Census <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Taeuber </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that officials have decided to hold a separate count, a few days before the regular national census, in an effort to count those living on the streets and in shelters. The homeless have become an increasingly visible part of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> society, but there are no concrete estimates of their numbers. On March 20, 1990, Census takers will visit emergency shelters, both public and private, and will go to various street locations which have been identified as places the homeless congregate, said <PERSON> Taeuber </PERSON>. The street search for the homeless will be conducted from 2 a.m. to 4 a.m., and shelters will be visited from 6 p.m. to midnight, she said. Census officials will be working with various groups and agencies that serve as advocates for the homeless, explained <PERSON> Taeuber </PERSON>, in order to determine in advance where to look for these people. In addition, the agency will encourage people with those groups, and the homeless themselves, to work as enumerators in the count. However, these workers will have to pass the same written exams and other criteria as all Census workers. Census day for most of the nation is April 1, 1990. The count of the homeless is being taken a few days early, however, because many shelters close at the end of March or beginning of April, <PERSON> Taeuber </PERSON> said. She added that the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> will not try to define who constitutes a homeless person. Instead it will merely issue counts of people living on the streets and those staying in various types of shelters.
</TEXT>
