<HEAD>US, Allies Try To Slow Argentine, Brazilian, North Korean Missiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its industrial allies are trying to slow the development of missiles in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and hope to have the cooperation of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in the global campaign against proliferation. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> confirmed on Monday that the seven allies, meeting in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> Sept. 8-9, exchanged expressions of concern about missile proliferation and technology transfers that might enhance <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s capability. Afterward, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> the same group registered concern in its deliberations about programs in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> may pursue the problem with Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> during their talks in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Thursday and Friday. In any event, the official said, Assistant Secretary of <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> will take up the issue at talks in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> next week with <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON>, senior Soviet arms control negotiator. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s attempt to extend the range of its Scud B missile should demonstrate to the Soviets the proliferation problem extends to their region, the official said. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s attempt to develop the Sonda IV missile is the other program the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> discussed with representatives of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the official said. `` It was an attempt to keep everybody up to date in the area,'' the official said. `` They did not adopt any special program. That's not the way it works. Meanwhile, spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON>, referring to the medium-range Condor II that <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> reportedly is developing with the help of <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, said `` the basic concern is that we do what we can to limit this kind of technology because it is the kind of technology that produces missiles that would be nuclear-capable.'' He said they also would exceed `` the range of parameters we established,'' meaning a range beyond 180 miles and a payload in excess of 1,100 pounds. The seven countries agreed last year that they would not export missiles or technology for them that went beyond these limits. Meanwhile, an <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> representative voiced concern about <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s launch Monday of a test satellite into orbit and said it meant the Arabs would have to strengthen their defenses. <PERSON> Clovis </PERSON> <PERSON> Maksoud </PERSON>, who represents the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said the satellite gave <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> `` a serious strategic leverage'' since the country already had the capability to fire long-range missiles. <PERSON> Maksoud </PERSON>, in an interview, stressed steps taken jointly by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to strengthen their strategic ties. He cited <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inclusion of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> in the program to develop a space-based defense against ballistic missiles and `` <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s record, which is replete with disclaiming nuclear capability. As a result, <PERSON> Maksoud </PERSON> said, the launching of a test satellite `` warrants enhancing Arab defensive capabilities'' so that any <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> negotiations produce a peaceful outcome `` rather than ratifying Israeli hegemony.'' The satellite is designed for communications purposes, but the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> official said it could be used to monitor <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s foes. `` We are deeply concerned that such a communications satellite can be modified into a spy system and, therefore, further enhance the strategic imbalance which the <LOCATION> American-Israeli </LOCATION> strategic agreement has introduced,'' <PERSON> Maksoud </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was not involved in any way with the Israeli program. `` We do n't have any details of the launch beyond what was reported by the Israelis,'' he said. A spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, Cmdr. <PERSON> Dugald </PERSON> <PERSON> Gillies </PERSON>, said American radars and sensors picked up the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> satellite shortly after launch. Its orbit has been calculated to have a high point of 716 miles and a low point of 155 miles, he said. `` It was launched early Monday Eastern Daylight Time and is in a near polar orbit,'' <PERSON> Gillies </PERSON> said. Defense officials at the Pentagon said they were unsure exactly what the satellite's payload included. `` But we're leaning toward more of an experimental communications package as opposed to a true spy satellite,'' said one source who spoke on condition of anonymity. `` This launch is impressive because it's a first, but I do n't think this particular satellite is going to offer much more ability to keep tabs on their neighbors,'' the source said <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> stressed that <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> leaders had given public assurances that their goal was `` peaceful purposes of space research and technological advancement.'' <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is the eighth nation to place a satellite into space. The country is generally believed to have nuclear capability.
