<SECOND>PM-Marilyn Quayle, Bjt,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marilyn Quayle: Husband's Strong-Willed Adviser Campaigns on Her
Own</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> has done `` 20 @ 20.'' Her husband <PERSON> Dan </PERSON>, the Republican running for the country's No. 2 job, has not. He sometimes stumbles over his words. She never does. He can freeze when a reporter asks an unexpected question. She is always prepared, and the only frozen look is the one she icily bestows on an unfriendly questioner. Mrs. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, who is on her first solo national campaign swing this week, is considered one of the stronger assets of her husband's campaign. Her skills, said a senior campaign official, have `` been recognized'' and she has been asked to travel independently, hooking up with the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> senator for joint appearances one or two days each week. At 39, Mrs. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> is a self-possessed woman whose flip hairdo and toothy smile evoke early <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>. She is a mother of three and a lawyer, although she has n't practiced for some years. As a political wife, she's strong willed, fiercely protective and her husband's most trusted adviser. On the campaign trail, she can be warm and cordial, quick with a handshake for her husband's supporters or a hug for children at a day care center. But she also can be cold and withdrawn, especially around reporters. A practiced campaigner, Mrs. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> nevertheless is unaccustomed to the <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan-like </PERSON> role she has played so far _ smiling pleasantly at her husband's side, applauding at the appropriate points. `` I've never sat listening to him give speeches and all of that. I always had my own schedule'' of campaigning, she said in a recent interview. She handles most situations with aplomb. When a precocious 4-year-old at a <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> day care center commented on Mrs. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s slightly protruding teeth as `` a little buck,'' Mrs. <PER