sts were <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Califano </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> secretary 1977-79; <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Finch </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> HEW </ORGANIZATION> secretary 1969-1970; <PERSON> Elliot </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> HEW </ORGANIZATION> secretary 1970-73; and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Schweiker </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> secretary 1981-83. Areas of agreement among panelists included: _ The health care delivery system does not match the population's _ Pregnant women can not get adequate health care _ For too many of those who need it, insurance is not available _ Too little is being spent on prevention of children's health problems _ There is a fragmentation of services which should be offered at central locations _ The federal government should take some responsibility in setting up above - standard day care
