<HEAD>Dress Code Aims at Ending Thefts, Rivalry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A high school made famous by <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> has banned gold chains, designer sunglasses or other expensive status symbols to prevent an expensive competition students ca n't afford, the principal says. `` I see and hear about the youngsters being shot over gold chains as they walk to and from school,'' <ORGANIZATION> Mumford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Principal </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Oden </PERSON> said. `` My kids -LRB- students -RRB- have been harassed. Recognizing that, I want to make sure that it does n't spill over into the school. The dress code established this school year also bans tank tops, jogging suits, snakeskin-adorned gym shoes and like finery at the 2,500-student, inner-city school, which gained fame through T-shirts <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> wore in the film `` <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> Cop.'' A student who violates the code gets a written notice, which is sent to his or her parents. Repeat offenses can result in a three-to five-day suspension. <PERSON> Oden </PERSON> said a 14-year-old student told him last year that she had heard a dress code was being considered and that she hoped one would be adopted. `` She said she could n't afford to purchase expensive things and felt bad when she could n't compete with her peers,'' the principal said. `` That troubled me, so I talked to other students and found out they felt the same way.'' Rivalry involving expensive clothing has sometimes turned violent. Two 17-year-old boys were wounded by gunfire last year after one was robbed of a blue sheepskin jacket. Three years ago, a <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> retailer threatened to discontinue a brand of gym shoes when a 13-year-old was shot in the chest after giving his gym shoes to five youths who demanded them. On a recent afternoon, some students were spotted near <LOCATION> Mumford </LOCATION> High wearing gold or other expensive jewelry and other banned items. They said they stashed it at school during the day, then wore it home. <PERSON> Oden </PERSON> said a student who did the same thing was assaulted by two boys who robbed her of two gold chains. He said he told other students of the incident at an assembly. <PERSON> Oden </PERSON> said he is encouraged by the students following the code. `` I invite you to stand out in the hall and I dare you to find any gold jewelry,'' he said. `` We've had to deal with some students, but we have not had any suspensions to this day. About 98 percent of my students adhere to the dress code to the letter.''
