<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>, at 87 the world's longest reigning monarch, received a blood transfusion after vomiting blood and was in stable condition at the Imperial Palace on Tuesday, palace officials and news reports said. But the respected <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> news agency, citing unidentified `` government sources,'' said at midday that the emperor appeared to be in critical condition. Officials would not confirm the report. The government decided Tuesday to place Crown Prince <PERSON> Akihito </PERSON>, 54, the emperor's eldest son, in charge of all matters of state until the emperor recovers, <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> head <PERSON> Kichiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Tazawa </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Tazawa </PERSON> told reporters after a regular Cabinet meeting that the Cabinet was expected to formally approve the appointment Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> said the government was considering whether to advise <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> members to remain at their offices and not leave <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. The emperor's death would plunge <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> into official mourning, for which there would be no modern precedent. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> has been on the throne since 1926, and older Japanese who grew up when he was considered divine revere him greatly. Those born after World War II tend to have less interest in the emperor, who renounced his divinity after the war. Court physicians were summoned to the palace in central <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> after the emperor vomited blood shortly before 10 p.m. -LRB- 9 a.m. EDT -RRB- Monday and they gave him a blood transfusion for four hours beginning at 12:30 a.m. Tuesday, the imperial official said, speaking on condition of anonymity. The doctors ruled out hospitalizing the aged emperor. Television and news service reports said <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> received 1.7 pints of blood during the transfusion and was fully conscious during the treatment. Following the transfusion, the emperor's temperature fell to about 98.6 degrees and his pulse was a normal 90 beats per minute, according to the imperial official. After two consecutive days of fever, <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s condition grew worse late Monday. Imperial officials said court phsycians found traces of jaundice in his blood and would perform minor surgery if the fever continued. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> suffered a 100.4 degree fever Sunday. Almost one year ago on Sept. 22, the emperor underwent an intestinal operation, and doctors found a hard, egg-size enlargement of the pancreas, which blocked the duodenum. Surgeons did not remove the blockage but performed a bypass around it. In recent weeks the emperor has suffered a cold, according to the imperial agency, and news reports last week said he has lost 20 pounds from his weight of 130 pounds before his surgery last year. <PERSON> Akihito </PERSON>, heir to the Chrysanthemum Throne that <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> has held since Christmas Day 1926, and Crown Princess <PERSON> Michiko </PERSON> came to the palace Tuesday morning. Nationally broadcast television reports showed limousines bearing members of the imperial family arriving at the palace to pay their respects. Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> visited early Tuesday to sign his name on a list of well-wishers, according to television reports.
