<HEAD>Dukakis Aides Accuse Bush Of Lies; Promise To Fight Back</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Aides to <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, incensed by what one called <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s misleading `` statistical hit-and-run,'' are organizing Democratic surrogates to respond more aggressively to the vice president's attacks, which in recent days have focused on the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> economy. That strategy was evident Monday when, within hours of a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> speech, the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign called on eight business leaders to meet with reporters to rebut <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s characterization of the Democratic nominee as an anti-business governor. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> advisers, frustrated by what they contend has been far too little scrutiny of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s attacks, promised similar events in the future. The latest salvos have particularly angered the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> camp because they center on the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> economy _ the backbone of the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> candidacy. `` Our view is that a candidate has an obligation to tell the truth to the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people,'' said <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Donnell </PERSON>, a senior <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> adviser. `` But <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has played fast and loose with the facts last week and he's doing it again this week. It's what we call statistical hit-and-run.'' Last week <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> charged that <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> taxpayers had suffered under <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and that the state was $ 7.4 billion in debt, a figure the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign cited to assert that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> since 1983 had amassed more debt than all the governors `` from the Pilgrims to <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>,'' his predecessor. The figures he cited to support the increased tax burden indeed showed that per-capita taxes increased in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> from 1983 to 1987 but failed to factor in record growth of personal income in the state during that period. Taxes were cut in those years _ mostly over <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' objections _ but the average <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> resident pays more taxes because he or she is earning more money. And while <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is authorized to issue bonds totaling $ 7.4 billion, the state's current bonded indebtedness is $ 3.9 million _ lower in inflation-adjusted dollars than the debt <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> inherited from King. `` The bottom line is that in taxes, across the board, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> citizens pay more than they did several years ago,'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodin </PERSON>. `` We're not going to back down one iota.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> continued his assault Monday, telling a <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> luncheon in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had an `` anti-business scheme'' and that the number of business bankruptcies in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> was up 23.7 percent during the first six months of the year while the national rate had fallen 23.5 percent. <PERSON> Goodin </PERSON> said the figures came from the <ORGANIZATION> Small </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aides said they had not seen those figures but again accused <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> of misrepresentation _ citing figures showing business failures in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> had declined by 28 percent since <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> became governor in 1983, and that they had occurred at less than half the national rate during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> presidency. `` We're running against a guy who kicked off his campaign in <LOCATION> Disneyland </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Gearan </PERSON>, referring to a Labor Day appearance there by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` He has Goofy as his economist or something and is throwing out daffy statistics. This is the kind of opponent we have and expected and we are prepared to run against.'' <PERSON> Gearan </PERSON>, citing <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>'s appearance on a weekend news program to support <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' views on defense and foreign policy, said leading members of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> would be called on to rebut some <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> charges while <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> business and industry leaders would address <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> comments about the state economy. `` My company has grown and prospered under the leadership of Governor <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>,'' <ORGANIZATION> Wang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> founder <PERSON> An </PERSON> <PERSON> Wang </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> supporter, told the Monday briefing. `` He created the atmosphere that made it possible for us to grow.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> will respond as well when he sees fit, said <PERSON> Gearan </PERSON>, who with other <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aides encouraged increased media scrutiny of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s statements. `` <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has a record of being wrong,'' <PERSON> O'Donnell </PERSON> said. `` Not only are we on notice but the press is on notice. He has consistently misrepresented the facts and not been accurate.'' <PERSON> Goodin </PERSON> rejected that characterization as `` nonsense.'' `` I think the big lie is that they are making <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> out to be some sort of economic miracle,'' <PERSON> Goodin </PERSON> said.
