<HEAD>43rd General Assembly Convenes As U.N. Chief Praises Peacemaking
Role</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEAD prospects uncertain. Assembly holds ceremonial opening
at 3:30 p.m. EDT, then elects new president.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> opens its 43rd General Assembly with enhanced prestige due to the Iran-Iraq truce and Afghan accords, a reputation that may tarnish once debate begins. Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> wryly observed that the world body, convening today, has high expectations to live up to. `` If the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> is treated as an angel, then we must remember that the halo that slips 10 inches is a noose,'' he said at a luncheon of the U.N. Correspondents Association on Monday. The session opens with the election of the president of the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> after a behind-the-scenes fight that has revived some lingering enmity from the 1982 <LOCATION> Falkland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> War between <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Dante </PERSON> <PERSON> Caputo </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> has campaigned hard against <LOCATION> Barbados </LOCATION>' <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> ambassador, <PERSON> Dame </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Nita </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrow </PERSON>, who <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has backed. Diplomatic sources said the race was too close to call, and there could be several secret ballots before one candidate wins a simple majority of the assembly's 159 voting member states. The outgoing president is <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Florin </PERSON>, from <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> has won progress and praise with its Iran-Iraq truce, Afghan accord, and other looming peace initiatives in southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION>. But the general debate that begins Monday may generate more heat than light. One fight is expected over a proposed address by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> on the 40th anniversary of its founding. Both it and communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> have non-voting observer status and can not speak before the assembly without an invitation. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and other nations back <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s speech But the Soviet bloc has opposed the move and sponsored a resolution Monday inviting <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to deliver an address. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has not sponsored either resolution but opposes a South Korean speech. On Monday, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is to deliver his final speech to the world body, which his administration has criticized over the years for bureaucracy, waste and an anti-Western bias. The Soviet foreign minister, <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>, and President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> also are to address the assembly. The session will hear 13 heads of state, six prime ministers and numerous foreign ministers. The assembly will again take up intransigent issues such as peace in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and the Palestinian uprising in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s occupied lands In his annual report released Monday, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> painted a cautiously optimistic picture of the organization, citing: _ the U.N.-mediated Afghanstan accords signed April 14 under which about 100,000 Soviet troops are leaving that nation; _ a U.N.-supervised cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war that began Aug. 20; _ the <LOCATION> Iran-Iraq </LOCATION> peace talks that opened Aug. 25; _ a U.N.-sponsored meeting between <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> and Turkish Cypriot leaders of divided <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>; _ initiatives for peace in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and neighboring <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and positive signs for a political settlement to the <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> noted continuing problems in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s enforcement of apartheid and the division of the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>. The secretary-general said the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> still faces a financial crisis, despite a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> promise to pay $ 144 million in arrears and hundreds of millions of dollars in other back dues for previous years and for peacekeeping funds. The Peruvian diplomat said the organization faces a cash shortage `` which threatens insolvency in the next few months, and the virtual depletion of reserves.'' He said he would ask the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> urgently to consider new ways of raising money, such as voluntary contributions, interest-free loans and changes in the scale of assessments.
