<HEAD>Fireworks Factory Blast Kills Five</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An explosion in a private fireworks factory killed five people, including the owners and their 12-year-old son, and injured nine, a newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> reported today The Guangming Daily said the Aug. 23 blast was triggered when the 12-year-old, who worked at the factory, mishandled fuses. He and the four other victims died in the hospital. The paper did not explain the delay in reporting the accident, the second fireworks explosion in fourth months in coastal <LOCATION> Zhejiang </LOCATION> province's <LOCATION> Congnan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. In June, an explosion at another factory injured 15 workers, including 13 children. Safety standards generally are low in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s more than 90,000 small-scale private and township-run fireworks factories, and accidents are common. The most recent government statistic says 644 fireworks factory employees were killed in accidents in 1986. Eighteen people died last December in a nearby <LOCATION> Jiangxi </LOCATION> province factory where untrained workers were instructed to cut the fireworks' fuses by hand. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has begun drafting workplace safety regulations but enforcement is lax.
</TEXT>
