<FIRST>r p PM-Debate-Talks     09-20 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Debate-Talks,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Bush Campaigns Spar on Debate Questioners</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> will step forward to take questions in their first presidential debate Sunday, but it remains unclear who will be asking those questions. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the Democratic hopeful, proposed Monday that the four commercial television network news anchormen be the moderator and panelists, sources familiar with the negotiations said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> candidate, had his own list of four possible peacekeepers and 10 questioners from both electronic and print journalism. By late Monday, the question of questioners was still being debated by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aides as the Sunday date for the face-off at <ORGANIZATION> Wake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> drew closer. The last-minute sparring is typical of presidential campaigns, complete with accusations that the other side is breaking their agreement not to talk about any of the arrangements. The first debate is sponsored by the parties' commission on debates. The second presidential debate, due Oct. 13 or Oct. 15 in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, is sponsored by the League of Women Voters. This most recent volley between the campaigns erupted Monday, when <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> called <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> to propose the four-anchor idea for all three debates. Sources who spoke only on the condition they not be identified said <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> suggested that the anchors from <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> and the Cable News Network be the moderators and questioners during both presidential debates and the vice president debate scheduled Oct. 5 in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>. That would mean CBS's <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rather </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Brokaw </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> and probably <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> would be on stage for all three events. And contacts were made with the news organizations to see if they would agree, one source said. ` This is a television event,'' said one <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aide of the idea. `` We want to do what we can to make it an event that people will pay attention to. We think that they anchors would make it a bigger event ... More people would watch it.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aides flatly rejected the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> idea of all the presidential debates as well as the vice presidential one. The idea is `` blatantly unfair to the print media and other television correspondents,'' said one <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aide. But a <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aide said that their proposal was still on the table, despite the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign's stance. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> source said the campaign responded later Monday with a list of four proposed moderators and 10 panelists. The source would not name any of them, saying only the list was made up of network anchors, network correspondents and print representatives. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> source also accused the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign of violating the agreement not to talk about such matters. `` We are operating under a written agreement of understanding not to discuss the negotiations surrounding'' debate details, said the aide. `` Obviously that has been violated,'' and thus the source gave the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign position on the matters. While pre-debate squabbling is normal, the difference this year is there is no third party _ such as the <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voters </ORGANIZATION> _ as the moderator of the pre-debate debate. The two political parties tried to wrest the debate sponsorship away from the league with the formation of the bipartisan debate commission. But the league _ which has sponsored debates in the past three presidential campaigns _ kept fighting for a role. When the two campaigns agreed to split sponsorship of the debates, that left them to deal more directly with each other on these pre-debate matters than in the past.
</TEXT>
