<HEAD>Army Scraps High-Level Biological Warfare Lab</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERN ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOOELE ARMY DEPOT, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to scrap plans for a high-level biological warfare test lab in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> has drawn praise from state officials, but an environmentalist says residents still ca n't rest easy. The <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> announced Monday it will no longer seek approval for the lab designed for experiments with genetically altered microbes or deadly micro-organisms for which there are no known antidotes. Instead, <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> officials said, they will downgrade the proposed `` biosafety level 4'' laboratory at Dugway Proving Ground to a new $ 5.3 million level-3 lab where scientists can experiment with biological agents for which there are vaccines or cures. `` The people of <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> are still at more risk,'' said <PERSON> Jeremy </PERSON> <PERSON> Rifkin </PERSON> of the Foundation on Economic Trends in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> `` It's easier for viruses to get out of this facility than the one they proposed. The chance of a micro-organism escaping is low. But if one does escape, it could be catastrophic.'' <PERSON> Rifkin </PERSON> said his organization, which brought legal action forcing the Army to conduct a more extensive environmental assessment of the proposed lab, would seek another injunction if the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> went ahead with its plans without a new environmental impact study. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Owen </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s deputy assistant secretary for installations and logistics, said the level-3 lab would be used for tests of materials and defenses against biological attack similar to those conducted at Dugway since the early 1950s in a lab that now is outdated. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s decision is based on an extensive evaluation of the requirements for biological defense,'' <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> said. `` Existing Army BL4 facilities will be used to satisfy any future needs for material testing that requires a containment level higher than BL3.'' The Army's original draft environmental statement, published in February, said the higher-level lab would be used only for level-3 experiments, but it did not rule out experiments with more exotic and deadly agents in the future. <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> said the final environmental impact statement due next spring would identify the level-3 lab as `` the preferred alternative for construction.'' The draft document had listed it only as a possible alternative, concluding a level-4 lab would be safer. <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>'s congressional delegation and Republican Gov. <PERSON> Norm </PERSON> <PERSON> Bangerter </PERSON> praised the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s decision. In March, <PERSON> Bangerter </PERSON> had vowed to block construction of a higher-level lab, including withholding state construction permits, and later met with <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> officials to seek a compromise. `` I appreciate the Army's new-found willingness to compromise with the people of <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> and negotiate with me as governor on matters which affect the state and its citizens,'' <PERSON> Bangerter </PERSON> said. The governor said he would announce within days the composition of a civilian-scientist oversight committee to monitor testing at the desert outpost 70 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` I will insist the open process continue and the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> shares with the people in the state information regarding what testing is being performed in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Bangerter </PERSON> said. During a public comment period that ended Aug. 2, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> received 107 comments, 103 of which opposed building the facility. <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> said the outcry over the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s initial plan was `` not the sole determining factor in the decision,'' but he added, `` we try to be good neighbors.'' `` There was never a decision to back down or away from, as such,'' he said. `` We did not have a decision prior to now.'' <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> said there are five higher-level containment labs in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> where the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> could conduct such tests, if needed, including its own lab at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Detrick </LOCATION>, Md. On Monday night, 100 people attended an <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> hearing at <ORGANIZATION> Tooele </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Depot </ORGANIZATION> on the draft environmental impact statement governing the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s biological defense research program. The document concluded that the program `` does not create significant adverse impacts on the quality of the environment'' and perceived risks are `` very much exaggerated.'' It also rejected the idea of a non-military management of the testing program, saying it would not mute controversies relating to such issues as genetic engineering, highly infectious organisms or aerosol testing. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> abandoned research into offensive biological weapons in 1969 and later signed a treaty banning their use or possession. The <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> continues to conduct research into defensive measures against biological warfare, such as masks and vaccines.
