<HEAD>First Talks In Three Months Break Off</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nicaraguan government and rebel leaders broke off their first talks in three months after failing to agree on a new site for resuming peace negotiations. President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> accused the rebels, known as Contras, of seeking to avoid negotiations in hopes of receiving new <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid. The rebel delegation rejected the government's demand that future talks resume in the Nicaraguan capital of <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>, chief rebel delegate <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferrey </PERSON> said after Monday's four-hour meeting. He said the rebels proposed <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> or the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> as the negotiating site. Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON>, head of the government delegation, said the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> were sticking by their position that the talks be held in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. Monday's meeting was called as a preliminary step to resuming high-level talks to end the 7-year civil war. Those negotiations broke down June 9. No date for another meeting was announced. In <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> on Monday night, <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> noted that his government had bowed to rebel demands to hold previous talks in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. He accused the rebels of deliberately trying to make negotiations impossible in a bid to receive renewed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Yankees </ORGANIZATION> are interested, through the Contras, in trying to show <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> has an intransigent position ... to approve military aid for the counterrevolutionaries. This is the objective,'' <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> declared. `` We should speak with -LRB- President -RRB- <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. We should speak to those who pay the gunslingers and not the gunslingers,'' he said in remarks broadcast by state-run radio. Ferrey renewed a rebel proposal that high-level talks be held Sept. 26-28, but not in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. His delegation also demanded the government release more than 40 opposition activists arrested during demonstrations in July and guarantee freedom of expression before further talks are held. For his part, <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> reiterated the government's demand that the Contras free 66 prisoners of war being held in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. In March, the two sides signed a preliminary cease-fure accord and agreed to seek a negotiated settlement to the conflict the government says has killed 28,000 Nicaraguans. The agreement called on the rebels to lay down their arms in exchange for democratic reforms. Shortly before peace talks broke off in June, the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> proposed a timetable for disarmament and political reforms. But the Contras rejected the plan, saying it did not go far enough. They demanded freedom for political prisoners and democratic reforms in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> before disarming. Direct <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid to the rebels ended Feb. 29. Non-lethal <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to the Contras is distributed only in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. About 9,000 rebel fighters have fled <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> during the past four months for base camps inside <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> to receive new supplies of uniforms and food.
