<HEAD>Teamsters Delay Candidate Endorsement Until Mid-October</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brotherhood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> is giving its members more time to vote on their presidential preference, putting off the union's possible endorsement of a candidate until mid-October. `` My guess is that we're not going to do any endorsement until our next board meeting Oct. 17,'' Teamsters spokesman <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> <PERSON> Zeller </PERSON> said Monday. <PERSON> Zeller </PERSON> said the 1.6 million-member union has extended until Sept. 30 the deadline for the rank and file to return poll ballots on presidential preferences that were mailed to them three weeks ago. <PERSON> Zeller </PERSON> said 10,000 to 12,000 of the ballots have been returned to <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>' headquarters here but have not been tallied. With the extended deadline, he said, the responses can not be tabulated and analyzed before the next meeting of the union's 18-member executive board Oct. 17-19 in <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION> The Teamsters were among three of the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION>'s 91 affiliated unions that abstained last month from the labor federation's overwhelming endorsement of Democratic nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> Until the death of former Teamster President <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Presser </PERSON> in June, union officials had expected the executive board to endorse <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. Several union officials have said the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s indictment of <PERSON> Presser </PERSON> in 1986 and a civil suit in June aimed at taking control of the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> as a corrupt organization have soured relations with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> The new Teamster president, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, is known to dislike <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. One Teamster official, speaking only on condition that he not be identified, said he does not expect the executive board to make any endorsement this year unless the rank-and-file poll shows overwhelming support for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. The Teamsters were the only major union to endorse <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in 1980 and 1984, although with less enthusiasm the second time. It made no endorsement in the 1976 race which <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> won against President <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>. Since 1952 the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> have endorsed four Democrats and four Republicans.
