 Share prices plunged today on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in apparent reaction to Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s failing health. The dollar edged up against the Japanese yen. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues shed 352.42 points or 1.26 percent to close at 27,548.58. The main index, which rapidly lost 169.20 points to move down to 27,731.80 points shortly after the market opened, kept declining afterwards. It was the fourth biggest one-day decline this year. In a moderate trading with volume on the first section estimated at 1 billion shares, stock prices were lower across the board except for a few print-related issues such as paper and pulp, said an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. `` Investors were mainly selling stocks trying to get ready if the worst happens to the emperor. Their concern was, for example, the stock market might be closed in that case,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity. <PERSON> Hirohita </PERSON>, 87, vomited blood Monday night, and was reported in stable conditon. The emperor also has been reported to have jaundice. Meanwhile, the dollar opened lower at 133.62 yen and finished the day's trading at 134.15 yen, up 0.35 yen from Monday's close. A dealer with <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> said the emperor's condition did not affect trading on the foreign exchange market. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency rose due to dollar-buying during the afternoon trading, the dealer added, also speaking on condition of anonymity.
