 The dollar was little changed in subdued European trading early today ahead of the release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic reports and a weekend meeting of the seven leading industrialized nations. Gold prices were higher. Dealers said they doubted that the final revision of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> gross national product figures for the second quarter, would stimulate the markets. Dealers were anticipating a 3.3 percent growth rate in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy. The August rate of inflation was due to be released later in the week. Dealers said market players were withdrawing to the sidelines ahead of Saturday's opening meeting in <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> of finance ministers of the <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seven </ORGANIZATION> industrialized democracies. `` The market is very calm and should stay so as long as the dollar is awaiting some new stimulus,'' said a dealer in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where the business day ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s begins, the dollar edged up 0.35 Japanese yen to a closing 134.15 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it fell back to 133.90 yen. Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday: _ 1.8690 West German marks, down from 1.8695 _ 1.5785 Swiss francs, down from 1.5793 _ 6.3545 French francs, up from 6.3520 _ 2.1080 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1100 _ 1,392.25 Italian lire, down from 1,393.50 _ 1.2192 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2194 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound held steady at $ 1.6785 dollars, unchanged Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 409.40 dollars a troy ounce, up from $ 409.30 dollars bid late Monday. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 410.40. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the noon bid price was $ 410.30, up from $ 408.50 b