 A police sergeant responding to a fatal shooting outside a housing project discovered that the victim was his own stepson in a tragedy that his commander called `` every cop's worst nightmare.'' Sgt. <PERSON> Lonnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>, 43, found the body of his 19-year-old stepson, <ORGANIZATION> Norris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Williams </ORGANIZATION>, on the sidewalk near the <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> project early Sunday. The teen-ager had been shot in the chest with a 9mm bullet and was pronounced dead at the scene. Less than six hours later, <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, 18, of <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> was arrested and charged with murder and possession of an illegal handgun. The two youths had had a long-running dispute, police said. `` It's every cop's worst nightmare,'' Capt. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harkins </PERSON>, commanding officer of the 75th Precinct, told <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newsday </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> is taking time off from work until he feels up to coming back, <PERSON> Harkins </PERSON> said. He described <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> as `` a nice, quiet man, a good cop.'' <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> joined the <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in 1969 and was promoted to sergeant in 1986. He has been assigned to the 75th Precinct for more than two years, and has received eight commendations and citations for outstanding police work. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> was the youngest of <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>' three stepsons.
