<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of people rallied in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> today, closing businesses and schools in a protest that followed a bloody clash between Armenians and Azerbaijanis in a disputed region of the southern <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Meanwhile, one of the 25 people who the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said had been hurt in Sunday's shootout died the next day, an editor of a <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> affiliate said. The clash occurred in the village of <LOCATION> Khadzhaly </LOCATION> in the predominantly Armenian <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> enclave of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. Armenian activist <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Popoyan </PERSON>, in a telephone interview from the Amenian capital of <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, said Armenians did not use weapons. He did not elaborate. An editor for Armenpress, the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> affiliate in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, said Monday that Azerbaijanis were the only ones carrying firearms. The executive committee of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>'s parliament was to meet today or Wednesday to discuss protesters' long-standing demands to annex <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Popoyan </PERSON> said. Armenians began campaigning in February for control of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> near the Turkish-Iranian border. Armenians make up 76 percent of the region's 162,000 people and have strong historical links to the enclave, which was made part of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> in 1923. Several thousand people gathered today in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>'s downtown square, an <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officer said, and were `` just standing around conversing.'' Police stepped up patrols in this city, said a duty officer at <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, speaking by telephone from <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Popoyan </PERSON>, a 46-year-old former political prisoner, said 1 million Armenians attended a rally in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> Monday night and demanded an emergency meeting of the republic's parliament, the Supreme Soviet. A deputy director of Armenpress, who spoke on condition his name not be used, said more than 250,000 people were at the demonstration. The protesters want the Supreme Soviet to demand the annexation of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Popoyan </PERSON> said. The body has made such a decision, but was rebuffed by the country's Supreme Soviet in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>'s president, <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> <PERSON> Voskanyan </PERSON>, told Monday's rally that parliament's executive committee would meet today or Wednesday to decide whether to call a full Supreme Soviet session, according to <PERSON> Popoyan </PERSON>. At Monday night's rally, demonstrators decided to continue a general strike that began Friday, according to <LOCATION> Popoyan </LOCATION>, and many businesses and schools were closed in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> today. He said the demonstrators decided to continue the walkout until the Supreme Soviet acts on their demands. A strike also has been reported in the main city of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION>. An Armenpress editor said Sunday's clash was touched off by reports that <PERSON> Azerbaijanis </PERSON> had stoned a busload of Armenians the previous day in the village. A 61-year-old carpenter injured in the shootout died Monday in a hospital, an editor of a <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> affiliate in <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> said by telephone from the republic's capital, <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION>. Both editors spoke on condition of anonymity. In <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Azerbaijani </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Abdul-Rahman </PERSON> <PERSON> Vezirov </PERSON> told local officials today the clashes were part of `` anti-social activities'' among some of the populace, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported. He said required stricter controls were needed to ensure order, the agency reported. Armenians are predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION>; most Azerbaijanis are Shiite Moslem. Armenians also differ linguistically and culturally from ethnic Azerbaijanis. At least 32 people, 26 Armenians and six Azerbaijanis, were killed in three days of rioting that began Feb. 28 in the <LOCATION> Azerbaijani </LOCATION> port of <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>. In July, central authorities in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> rejected the annexation demand and instead approved a plan to redress Armenians' grievances of poor housing, hospitals, schools and Armenian cultural facilities in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>.
