<HEAD>County Board OKs AIDS Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Cook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> has voted to adopt a policy allowing county hospital patients to refuse to be treated by people with the AIDS virus, but the hospital has not developed a way to make the policy work. The county board, which also serves as the hospital board of directors, voted 15-2 Monday to adopt the policy that would make the hospital the first in the nation to give patients that right, officials said. `` Our reaction is one of dismay,'' Dr. <PERSON> Lonnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bristow </PERSON>, a trustee of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said last week, after the board's <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> approved the policy. `` There has been no case in this country of a patient contracting the AIDS virus from a health-care worker,'' <PERSON> Bristow </PERSON> said. No effective date was announced for the policy, which the hospital must still determine how to put into practice. The policy covers hospital workers who `` routinely provide direct patient care,'' including doctors and nurses. Acquired immune deficiency syndrome destroys the body's defenses against disease, leaving a person prey to life-threatening infections and certain cancers. AIDS has struck more than 72,000 people in this country since 1979 and killed more than 40,000 of them, according to the national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. The virus that causes the incurable and fatal disease is believed to be spread through sexual intercourse, shared hypodermic needles and from infected mothers to their infants before or during birth.
