readers.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RON HARRIST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vandals carved racial slurs on doors and splashed paint on an entry-way floor at the home of <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s first black congressman since Reconstruction, who is running for a second term this fall An upset <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Espy </PERSON> took time off from his 2nd District campaign today to repair the damage to his home in this town a few miles north of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. `` Sure, it makes you angry,'' he said. `` We've come a long way in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, but cases like this remind you how far we've got to go.'' <PERSON> Espy </PERSON>, a Democrat who faces Republican <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> in November, said his major concern was for his family. `` I'm the congressman. I have the record and I have my performance to defend and I can defend it,'' <PERSON> Espy </PERSON> said. `` I'm the congressman, not my wife, my brother or my children.'' <PERSON> Espy </PERSON> said his wife discovered the vandalism when she returned home with her children late Monday. `` My son is 5 and my daughter is 8 and I had to explain to them the history of race relations in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` They had carved the word ` Nigger' on two doors and I had to tell my children what that meant and why somebody would do that. It was not an easy thing to do. `` If someone wants to come after me, let them come, but I want them to leave my family alone.'' The congressman said the racial slurs were carved on doors in the covered entry-way leading into the house and a garage area. He said the letters were cut into the doors near the top, along with `` <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Con'' _ apparently referring to congressman. He said plants in the entry-way had been uprooted and paint dashed on the floor and on some of the plants. <PERSON> Espy </PERSON> said both doors were locked when his family arrived, and there apparently had been no attempt get inside. He said police were called and were investigating. Madison Police Chief <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukes </PERSON> said his officers had filed a report on the vandalism and an investigation was under way. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON>, chairman of the state <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, called for a full investigation of the incident. `` I hope this campaign does not degenerate into that level of activity,'' he said. `` I think <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> has gone a long way in erasing a negative image it has had outside the state. `` <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Espy </PERSON> has been a good congressman for this state and he has done a whole lot to improve <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s image,'' he said. `` I hope we are not going to allow a few narrow-minded people to take us back to a period we have gone through.'' <PERSON> Espy </PERSON> said he had received threatening calls in the past, `` but you always expect those. There has not been an increase in those calls, and this is the first time something like this has happened.'' `` I think most Mississippians would be upset to hear something like this has happened,'' he added, `` but we all realize there are still some ignorant people running around. We also realize that in public life, we are prone to attack.''
