<HEAD>Doctor With AIDS Sues Hospital, Doctors, City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A doctor who claims she contracted the AIDS virus after being accidentally pricked by a discarded needle in a hospital patient's bedding is suing the hospital, the city and two other doctors for $ 175 million. In papers filed Friday in trial-level state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Veronica </PERSON> <PERSON> Prego </PERSON>, 30, claims she was infected in January 1983 at <LOCATION> Kings </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>. The syringe needle had been used to draw blood from an AIDS patient, she said. At the time, Prego, a native of <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and a graduate of a medical school there, was working as an unsalaried aide to a hospital intern, Dr. <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Fogel </PERSON>, who is one of the defendants. Prego alleges that <PERSON> Fogel </PERSON>, who was treating the AIDS patient, `` negligently and improperly'' put three discarded needles on the patient's bedding _ one of which stuck Prego as she was cleaning up. She charges that <PERSON> Fogel </PERSON>, and later hospital officials, assured her they did n't know of any cases `` where a health care worker contracted AIDS by means of a needle stick.'' Such contamination recently has been shown to be possible. Prego also claims that the city's <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospitals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> did not supply any puncture-resistant disposal units for the contaminated syringes and needles. The suit also names <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Landsman </PERSON>, a doctor who had conducted a state-sponsored survey of health and hospital employees working with patients suffering from acquired immune deficiency syndrome. She said <PERSON> Landsman </PERSON> violated her right to confidentiality by informing hospital administrators about her condition. <PERSON> Janice </PERSON> <PERSON> Kabel </PERSON>, a lawyer representing the city, the <ORGANIZATION> HHC </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Fogel </PERSON>, said her clients have denied all substantive charges. She declined to comment further. The state attorney general's office, which is representing <PERSON> Landsman </PERSON>, also declined to comment.
