<DATELINE>NASHUA, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 On his last day in office, Education Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> today praised the tradition of strong local control in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> schools and downplayed the importance of kindergarten for youngsters. `` It would be a shame for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> to veer toward state control of education when we are telling other states to emulate <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said at a news conference. He cited just-released national statistics on <ORGANIZATION> Scholastic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aptitude </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tests </ORGANIZATION> as evidence that local control works. Average scores for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> students were tops nationally among the 22 states in which 40 percent or more of the students took the tests, which are widely used in college admissions. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, who appeared at the news conference with Republican gubernatorial candidate <PERSON> Judd </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON>, was asked to comment on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>'s status as the only state not to require kindergarten and <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON>'s opposition to state-mandated kindergarten. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> did not answer directly, but said, `` There is no research that conclusively proves that kindergarten gives kids a jump. `` Yes, kindergarten is desireable,'' he said, `` but a good first, second and third grade is more important than a good kindergarten.'' He added: `` No one suggests that <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION>'s education system is perfect. The general decline in education seen in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is seen in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, but <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, more than many other states, is on the right track'' trying to reverse the trend. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> went from <LOCATION> Nashua </LOCATION> to <PERSON> Hollis </PERSON>, where he was to briefly teach reading and speak to an assembly at the <ORGANIZATION> Hollis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, one of 287 winners nationwide in the <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s school recognition program He was also scheduled to go to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> today for his last official appearance as education secretary. Afterward, he planned to go hiking in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>.
