<HEAD>Independence Referendum For Western Sahara Annnounced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Security Council unanimously voted today to approve an independence referendum for <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION>, where Marxist guerrillas haven been battling <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>'s occupation forces for 13 years. The 15-0 <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> vote approved the appointment of a special representative of the secretary-general to monitor a referendum that would result in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION>'s independence or affiliation with <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>. Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> reminded the members of the council that on Aug. 30, representatives of the Polisario independence movement and <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> met with him in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> to approve the referendum and peace plan, with certain reservations. `` The proposals aimed at the restoration of peace in the region provide a framework for the conclusion of a cease-fire and the establishment of conditions necessary for the organization of a credible referendum,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief. `` The referendum will be organized and monitored by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in cooperation with the Organization of African Unity,'' he said. The organization has played a major role in arranging the dialogue between Polisario and <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said a special representative from his office, a civilian unit, a military unit and a security unit would work for peace in the area. `` The proposals also provide that the Kingdom of <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> will carry out an appropriate, substantial and gradual reduction of its troops in the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahra </LOCATION>,'' with remaining soldiers to be barracked under the supervision of <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> military observers. Polisario's fighters would also be quartered under <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> supervision. The Marxist-led Polisario movement of about 8,000 fighters has been battling for the independence of <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> since <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s colonial administration withdrew in 1975-76, and Moroccan occupation troops took over the phosphate-rich desert territory in northwest <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> More than 10,000 people have died in the nearly 13-year-old guerrilla war, which has cost <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> up to $ 2 million a day to fight. <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> covers about 110,000 square miles. Its population was set at 76,000 in 1974, during the last Spanish colonial census. Under the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> plan, only people born in the territory may vote in the referendum. Determining who is eligible will be a major chore for the referendum monitors. Polisario claims about 165,000 eligible Western Saharans live in its refugee camps near <LOCATION> Tindouf </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, which funds and shelters Polisario, but <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> says they are not eligible. <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> claims that 90 percent of the 150,000 residents of Moroccan-occupied sections of <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> are eligible, but <PERSON> Polisario </PERSON> says two-thirds of them are Moroccan immigrants.
