 <PERSON> Edde </PERSON> is acceptable to Moslem parliament deputies. His nomination will create an atmosphere of democratic competition within <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. This is what we want to preserve,'' said <PERSON> Sfeir </PERSON>'s spokesman, who demanded anonymity <PERSON> Edde </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> on Saturday that if elected, he will first seek an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> withdrawal from a self-designated security zone in south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, then ask the Syrians to leave. He warned that unless he succeeds in forcing the Israelis out, he would not return to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and would ask <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> to elect another president. Syrian-backed Moslem and leftist leaders have threatened to declare a separate republic in territory they control if <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON> seeks to resolve the crisis by appointing a <ORGANIZATION> Maronite </ORGANIZATION> prime minister to head a caretaker <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>. According to an unwritten national covenant dating to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s independence from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in 1943, the president should be a Maronite, house speaker a Shiite, and prime minister a Sunni Moslem Christian deputies boycotted a session at Villa Mansour Aug. 18, preventing <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> from mustering a quorum of 51 voters to elect a president. The only serious candidate at the time was Syrian-backed former president <PERSON> Suleiman </PERSON> <PERSON> Franjieh </PERSON>. Christians rejected him as too closely aligned with <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>. Moslem politicians charged that the main Christian militia was working at <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s bidding to trying to undermine the elections. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, the main power broker in