ON> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> considered establishing ties with <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION> in the 1960s but did not want to offend the Nationalist Chinese government on <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, which claims <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION> as part of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> broke ties with the Nationalists in 1979 and recognized the government in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Mongolian diplomats discussed establishing ties in the 1970s, but <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION> broke off the talks unexpectedly and new efforts began only in 1986, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said.
