<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Security forces in <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> have executed hundreds of unarmed civilians during anti-rebel operations this summer, and political prisoners are systematically tortured, a human rights group said in a report Wednesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> report says human rights have been `` persistently violated'' during President <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Siad </PERSON> <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>'s 19 years in power and that violations have intensified recently in countering rebel groups. `` Between several hundred and as many as 1,000 people have been summarily executed'' by government forces in northern regions since heavy fighting began in May, said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, a spokesman for the international organization. The killings, sometimes during house-to-house searches for Ethiopian-backed rebels, appeared aimed at terrorizing civilian sympathizers, he said. An estimated 200 prisoners also have been executed after summary trials in the last three years, he said. The London-based organization said it had compiled evidence of `` a consistent pattern'' of torture, arbitrary arrests and unfair trials of suspected government opponents. Torture victims said they were subjected to electric shocks and sexual assault, wounded with knives, suspended upside conducted house-to-house searches and `` arbitrarily killed many people,'' it said. Foreign relief agency workers reported 21 people were dragged from their homes and shot to death in separate incidents on May 31 and June 1, it said. `` These were all deliberate extrajudicial executions of alleged political opponents as distinct from the indiscriminate heavy casualties caused by the battle in the town or subsequent bombardment by the government forces,'' the report said. <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> said the 600,000 people of <LOCATION> Hargeisa </LOCATION> `` by and large were fleeing and the town is now virtually empty.'' `` There seem to be deliberate attacks on civilians -LRB- in urban areas -RRB-, but the security forces are n't sufficiently organized to sweep through the countryside,'' he said. <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> said a British reporter accompanying government troops during anti-rebel offensives this summer estimated that between 30,000 and 50,000 people have been killed in mainly aerial bombardments. The report said many prisoners held solely for the non-violent expression of their beliefs have been kept for years in deplorable conditions, often incommunicado and without proper medical aid. <PERSON> Yusuf </PERSON> <PERSON> Osman </PERSON> <PERSON> Samantar </PERSON>, a lawyer and former member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, has been in prison without charge for nearly 19 years, while <PERSON> Safia </PERSON> <PERSON> Hashi </PERSON> <PERSON> Madar </PERSON>, an employee of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> relief agency and a former science lecturer, was jailed for life in 1986 for `` membership of a subversive organization,'' the report said. Others include parliamentarians, doctors, clerics, businessmen, students and refugees, it said.
