<HEAD>Security Tight As Israelis Fast On Yom Kippur</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Large contingents of police were deployed in mixed Jewish-Arab areas Tuesday as Israelis started the 25-hour fast of Yom Kippur, the day of atonement and the most sacred holiday on the Jewish calendar. Traffic on the nation's highways came to a halt, commercial flights were suspended and the border with <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and bridges to <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> were closed. State-run <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> and television and <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> stopped transmitting, the only day of the year they do so. Yom Kippur came during a period of unprecedented conflict between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the 1.5 million Palestinians in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. Over the past nine months, more than 265 Palestinians and six Israelis have been killed in what has come to be known as the intefadeh, Arabic for uprising. To prevent violence, police stepped up security in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>'s mixed neighborhoods and other Jewish-Arab areas of the country. The army announced that as a security precaution Palestinians from the occupied territories would be barred from entering <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> between 2 p.m. Tuesday and 8 p.m. Wednesday. Yom Kippur ends the `` Ten Terrible Days'' during which, according to Jewish faith, <PERSON> God </PERSON> decides who will live through the coming year and who will die. During this period from the onset of the Jewish New Year until Yom Kippur, Jews bless each other with the greeting `` <PERSON> Gmar </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatima </PERSON> <PERSON> Tova </PERSON> _ May you be inscribed in the book of life.'' Before sundown, religious Jews shed leather shoes and belts and don white robes to prepare for the <LOCATION> Kol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nidre </LOCATION> service, the special prayer for forgiveness and life, which begins Yom Kippur. Early Tuesday, many Jews went to stores and markets to carry out the ancient rite of kapparot. Waving the chickens over their head, the penitents prayed that their sins would be transferred to the sacrificial chickens. Afterwards, the chickens were slaughtered. Stores, commercial and government offices, and public transportation shut down early to give workers time to prepare for the fast. A survey by the Hadashot daily indicated that 69 percent of Israeli Jews would fast even though the regularly observant portion of the population is estimated at only about 20 percent. In a reflective article on Yom Kippur in the left-wing daily `` Davar,'' columnist <PERSON> Amnon </PERSON> <PERSON> Dankner </PERSON> wrote: `` For many free and wild souls, Yom Kippur is their last link with <ORGANIZATION> Judaism </ORGANIZATION>, in which not only the religious intent is important. It is more like taking part in a sporting event which measures willpower, restraint, and even spirituality.'' Tuesday also marked the 15th anniversary of the 1973 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war which began on Yom Kippur when Egyptian and Syrian armies thrust through Israeli lines in the occupied <LOCATION> Sinai </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Desert </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Golan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION> and briefly threatened to invade <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> itself. On the eve of Yom Kippur, bereaved families layed wreaths and flowers at the gravesides of the 3,000 Israeli troops who died in the 1973 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war. Israeli newspapers printed reminiscences and commentaries about the war. <ORGANIZATION> Davar </ORGANIZATION>'s editor, <PERSON> Hanna </PERSON> <PERSON> Zemer </PERSON>, recalled that Egyptian President <PERSON> Anwar </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON> had offered <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> a territorial settlement in 1971 and drew parallels between those days and today. `` Before the Yom Kippur war, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> did not agree to withdraw from the Suez Canal. And that was not the only instance which showed that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> knows how to compromise ... only after paying the price for the stubborness which preceded it. We always come to the right conclusions too late.''
