<FIRST>u w AM-HomelessReport Bjt   09-20 0726</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless Report, Bjt,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless Panelists Wanted Stronger Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A report that termed homelessness a `` national disgrace'' was watered down and should have contained even stronger language and more specific recommendations, say members of the group that worked on the study for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vladeck </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> and head of the 13-member committee that prepared the study, said the academy refused to include a strong supplemental statement. `` The report, as it now stands, basically, was rejected by a majority of the committee because they felt it was not strong enough,'' <PERSON> Vladeck </PERSON> said. The edited final report `` did not allow us to express our outrage, our anger and our dismay at what we studied,'' complained <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>, a panel member and the head of <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homeless </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` Those who served on the panel ... were a little disturbed that we were not able to go into more detail on the problems of the homeless and some of the corrective measures that should be taken,'' added <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Stark </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lawyer and panel member who joined in signing a six-page supplemental statement issued by <PERSON> Vladeck </PERSON>'s office in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Despite the complaints, <PERSON> Vladeck </PERSON> raised the prospect that the material in the supplemental statement actually generated more attention by being left out of the official report than if it had been included. Faced with a choice of leaving out their strongest comments and issuing no report at all, the majority chose to permit the Academy to issue the bulk of the study and then make public their supplement independently, he explained. `` And frankly,'' he added, `` I think we wound up getting more publicity than we would have if it was buried in the report.'' The supplemental statement called for a restoration of federal support for low-income housing to 1981 levels, criticising the sharp cuts in these programs in recent years. It also urged a minimum wage at a level which would make decent housing possible in most cities and called for the federal government to be the guarantor of last resort in health care. `` The way you do away with homelessness is to provide homes,'' commented Stark, a former undersecretary at the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. The panelists were `` concerned that not enough emphasis was put on the plight of homelessness, in terms of just a statistical study,'' <PERSON> Stark </PERSON> said. `` I think the Academy is right in one sense,'' he added. `` They want all their reports to be as scientific and objective as possible.'' But, he said, once he had visited shelters and met the homeless and people who work with them, he realized that more was needed in this report. The group `` felt that the tone was important, as well as the substance, and this was not an issue where one can be comfortable being as bland as such reports tend to be,'' said <PERSON> Vladeck </PERSON>. Dr. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Press </PERSON>, former science adviser to President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and head of the independent <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> since 1981, was quoted in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> as saying the supplementary statement had been rejected because it was `` polemical and emotional.'' Press' office said he was not available Tuesday and referred calls to the Academy's <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, which organized the study as requested by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. At that <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, Dr. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> termed the official report `` strong,'' but said some of the specific recommendations were `` not sufficiently scholarly and documented to be included.'' The panel members `` were appalled at what they saw'' in their research, <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> said. He said academy reviewers agreed with many of the panel's opinions, but felt they needed more detailed economic analyses before they could be published officially `` The committee members endorsed the -LRB- official -RRB- report, and were at liberty to release their own statement elsewhere, which they have just done,'' he added. The official 242-page report portrays a homeless population not only of alcoholics and former mental patients, but one with growing numbers of children and families scraping out a dismal existence in rural communities. It calls children under 18 the fastest growing group among the nation's homeless and says this is `` nothing short of a national disgrace that must be treated with the urgency that such a situation demands.''
