<BYLINE>Endangered Squirrel On National Forest Land Targeted For Ski Resort
^By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An endangered species of flying squirrels and a virgin stand of red spruce are in the way of a developer's plan to turn a section of national forest into a $ 100 million ski resort. Environmentalists are mounting forces to oppose a proposal by <ORGANIZATION> Laurel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Creek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to build a resort community on the north slope of <LOCATION> Big </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Spruce </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION>, which overlooks the <ORGANIZATION> Cranberry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wilderness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> in eastern <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. The developer is negotiating with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to swap another piece of forestland for the Big Spruce land. `` We're concerned about the precedent here, of swapping really pristine land at the call of an out-of-state developer,'' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Wimmer </PERSON>, conservation chairwoman for the <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Laurel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> officials joined with Gov. <PERSON> Arch </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> last week to announce the development, which has sold 100 club memberships already, starting at $ 15,000 each. The governor claimed <ORGANIZATION> Laurel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Creek </ORGANIZATION> could create as many as 2,300 jobs in four years, counting spin-off services. Building lots will cost between $ 100,000 and $ 500,000, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said. But <ORGANIZATION> Laurel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Creek </ORGANIZATION> does not yet own the heart of its project _ the top of the mountain, which has an elevation of 4,695 feet. Without it, officials said Monday, the resort would have no long ski runs. Joined with 1,000 to 2,000 acres of land <LOCATION> Laurel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> already owns, the company would create a 2,300-acre complex with two golf courses, 32 ski runs, seven restaurants, lodges, cabins and houses. The mountaintop is a scarce habitat for the Northern Virginia flying squirrel, which lives in only a few areas of the state. The rust-colored, palm-sized animals roam the woods at night, gliding among the tree tops. The flying squirrels have disappeared over most of their <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> range for unknown reasons, but environmentalists blame the decline on a loss of habitat. The squirrels like mature red spruce stands, which are experiencing problems in the region. `` The spruce decline along the whole Appalachian corridor is very serious. It is becoming very scarce,'' <PERSON> Wimmer </PERSON> said. `` These areas need to be set aside.'' She said she also is waiting for the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to check the mountain for other endangered species, including the Cheat Mountain salamander, which lives in red spruce forests. Local trout fishermen also are concerned the resort would pollute Day Run, a trout stream, and in turn hurt the <LOCATION> Williams </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Cranberry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, which flows through nationally-protected wilderness areas. And conservationalists have another problem _ the way the matter has been handled. While the development was announced publicly last week, it was revealed that the corporation began talking privately with the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> a year ago a land swap. `` We feel there's been way too much work done without local input on this,'' <PERSON> Wimmer </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Trochlil </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> office in <ORGANIZATION> Elkins </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> Laurel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> had made no firm trade offers. To be acceptable, the land must match Big Spruce's stands of red spruce, he said. He said there was no available figure on how much of the mountain would be cut for ski slopes. He said the mountain is not a wilderness area, and that three to four Forest Service-supervised logging operations already are cutting trees in the national forest. <LOCATION> Laurel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> officials did not return repeated telephone messages left this week.
