<HEAD>West Germany Building On Decades Of Good Ties With Iran</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Building on decades of good ties with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> is seeking a greater business and diplomatic role in the country now that a cease-fire has been declared in the Iran-Iraq war. West German optimism toward <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> _ which sends its students to be educated in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and buys more goods from this country than any other _ grew after the recent release of West German hostage <PERSON> Rudolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordes </PERSON> from his pro-Iranian Lebanese kidnappers on Sept. 12. Germans have long felt what one expert calls a `` post-Romantic interest'' in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. A sector of the West German popular press provides constant coverage of the doings of <PERSON> Soraya </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakhtiary </PERSON>, once married to the shah of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Unlike the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other countries that broke off or curtailed ties with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> after <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> came to power in 1979, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> kept its relations active. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hans-Dietrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> credited those contacts with success in gaining the release of <PERSON> Cordes </PERSON> and promised to use that goodwill to try to win freedom for other Western hostages in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> held by pro-Iranian kidnappers. `` Since the time of the German kaisers at the end of the 19th century, there have been good relations, politically, economically and culturally -LRB- with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> -RRB-,'' said <PERSON> Dieter </PERSON> <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>. Less than two days after <PERSON> Cordes </PERSON>' release, the <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> announced that its No. 2 official, <PERSON> Dieter </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Wuerzen </PERSON>, was heading to <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> for a four-day visit to explore further business possibilities. `` But the announcement was just a coincidence,'' <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON> said in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, adding that the trip had been planned in advance. `` West German companies have a good chance of taking part in construction and reconstruction projects after the war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Welt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sonntag </ORGANIZATION> newspaper cited the <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Survey </ORGANIZATION> as saying reconstruction contracts for <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> could total $ 50 billion. `` When the weapons in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> went silent, German businessmen began to make their calculations,'' the newspaper added. <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON> cautioned that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s hard currency shortage would make foreign payments difficult. He said West Germans respect Iranians as trading partners _ despite the country's radical and sometimes fanatic image. Despite a trading decline due to the Iran-Iraq war, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> continues to import more goods from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> than from any other country, according to the <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> German </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. In 1987, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> sold $ 1.5 billion of goods to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, including motor vehicles, heavy machinery and electronic products. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> also imported $ 500 million worth of goods from <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. While West German law strictly forbids the shipment of weapons to areas of conflict, there are occasional reports of such material reaching <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. In May 1987, the Hamburg-based <ORGANIZATION> Der </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Spiegel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION> said a government-owned factory near <LOCATION> Wiesbaden </LOCATION> was exporting machines used for making ammunition to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. A book published in July alleged that <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> airport had become a transfer hub for shipment of weapons to the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, including <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Airport officials quickly denied the allegations, which were in a book written by West German journalist <PERSON> Juergen </PERSON> <PERSON> Roth </PERSON>.
