<HEAD>Carcasses Of 73 Wild Horses Found In Nevada Desert</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Carcasses of 73 wild horses have been discovered in an isolated section of central <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> and authorities believe they were gunned down, a <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said Tuesday. Federal investigators were tipped by a person who was questioned about an earlier rifle slaughter of 44 horses. The two sites are 30 miles apart. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, bureau spokesman, said a helicopter crew Monday identified 73 piles of bones and other evidence. The spokesman said ground crews were headed into the remote area to verify the cause of death of the horses but the evidence so far `` leads us to believe they were shot.'' He said the carcasses and bones of the horses were strewn along an area one to two miles wide and about eight miles long, apparently gunned down over a six-month period starting about one year ago. <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said the person who led investigators to the grisly discovery is n't being identified. He also declined to comment on whether there are any firm leads in either of the horse slaughters. He said local authorities, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney and the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> have been notified about the latest case, and land management employees have been told to `` increase their looking and try to spot any similar tragedies.'' <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said the carcasses were n't spotted immediately because crews who fly the area making horse counts `` fly at higher elevations and watch for dust clouds and movement.'' He said the maximum penalty for shooting a wild horse is a fine of $ 2,000 and a year in prison for each killing. More than 38,000 wild horses now run the open range of 10 western states, up from about 17,000 when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1971 made it a crime to harrass or kill wild horses on public lands. <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> has up to 28,000 wild horses, according to estimates. At the turn of the century there were some 2 million wild horses in the West, but they were relentlessly hunted by cowboys and `` mustangers'' in trucks and airplanes. The animals were slaughtered for pet food and glue.
