<DATELINE>BLOOMFIELD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years have been great for the flag business, says a member of the family that owns the nation's largest flag-making company `` The flag market usually has ups and downs, but it's been a steady incline since the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration came aboard,'' said <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Beard </PERSON>, vice presidant of <ORGANIZATION> Annin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. The fourth-generation co-owner and his brother, <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON>, opened one of their New Jursey factories Tuesday to Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who has mentioned the company often in contending that the administration has revived patriotic fervor. `` My friends, flag sales are doing well and <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is doing well,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said in front of a crowd of about 250, many of them <ORGANIZATION> Annin </ORGANIZATION> employees, in a flag-waving rally across the street from the old brick factory. <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Beard </PERSON>, whose brother joined <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on the rostrum, said the company has enjoyed a sales increase of roughly 25 percent in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years. <ORGANIZATION> Annin </ORGANIZATION> is one of a handful of major companies making the stars and stripes. <PERSON> Beard </PERSON> said he could not provide exact sales figures. He credited <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> for the steady growth of his company, which has expanded from three to five plants during <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s term. `` I think his patriotism has stirred flag sales,'' <PERSON> Beard </PERSON> said. `` He's increased pride in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' While <LOCATION> Annin </LOCATION> has supplied flags for inaugurations, the Apollo 11 moon flight, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and the armed forces, everyday citizens still account for the bulk of sales, <PERSON> Beard </PERSON> said. He said the Bloomfield factory each week makes about 30,000 of the small flags that have lately become common fare at patriotic celebrations. In addition, about 7,000 to 10,000 of the 3-by-5-foot flags commonly displayed by homeowners are produced each week at the factory, where women operate machines by hand, starting at minimum wage. In another flag-interest indicator, the federal government last year satisfied more than 109,000 requests to briefly fly flags over the nation's Capitol and then ship them to people. The requests numbered just 43,011 in 1979, a clerk said. While <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> deserves credit for the sales trend, <PERSON> Beard </PERSON> said this year's unusually strong September might also have something to do with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign. Labor Day usually marks a fast drop in flag buying, but demand has held steady in 1988, <PERSON> Beard </PERSON> said. The company found out about <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s visit about a week ago, and quickly arranged five buses to haul in employees from its three other <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> locations, <PERSON> Beard </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Annin </ORGANIZATION> also has a plant in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. Despite the good business of recent years, <PERSON> Beard </PERSON> said he's spotted a less-welcome trend: an influx of the red-white-and-blue from factories in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> Those countries' lower labor costs enable them to sell flags at a lower price and American producers are starting to feel the pinch, <PERSON> Beard </PERSON> said.
