<FIRST>r w AM-Pesticides     09-20 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pesticides,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Approves Eight-Year Pesticide Safety Deadline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved stepped-up pesticide regulation Tuesday, voting to set an accelerated, eight-year deadline for completion of safety reviews of hundreds of chemicals used by farmers to protect crops. The measure, approved and sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on a voice vote, amounts to a bare-bones bill without groundwater-protection and other contoversial features urged by environmentalists. `` This is the art of the possible, this will not satisfy hardly anyone but this is what we can do at this point,'' <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman E. `` Kika'' de la <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said in urging approval. He said lawmakers could return to the tougher issues in the future. The bill calls for completion of hundreds of safety reviews by the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> within eight years. The process is designed to end use of the most hazardous chemicals and limit utilization of others that present health dangers. The reviews have been in progress since the mid-1970s but without a deadline. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> estimates that at the current pace of about two dozen a year the task would not be completed until 2024. The bill would largely end indemnities to pesticide makers whose products have been ordered off the market for safety reasons. Thus far, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has been forced to pay $ 20 million to buy up supplies of banned pesticides. Provisions of the bill call for fees paid by manufacturers ranging from $ 50,000 to $ 150,000 to finance the reviews. The industry and the agency would share the cost of storage and disposal under the measure, which would reauthorize for three years the 1947 Federal Insecticide, Fungicide and Rodenticide Act. Environmentalists say the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has been dragging its feet on the safety reviews because it lacks the money to pay the indemnities. The act has been due for reauthorization since 1983 but squabbling among environmentalists, labor and the farm lobby have frozen action. `` We have had difficulty in times past in trying to make this happen,'' Rep. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>, D-Calif., told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Farmers have been highly suspicious of legislation they fear would ban or raise the cost of pesticides, which arose out of World War II chemical warfare research and now represent a fundamental element of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agriculture. `` Certainly with regard to agriculture, the efficient and judicious use of pesticides is crucial to the safety of the food supply that we enjoy today,'' declared Rep. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Grandy </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION>. Government research, however, has shown that some pesticides can cause cancer and other severe health problems. Environmentalists have been calling for tighter regulation since 1962 when naturalist <PERSON> Rachel </PERSON> <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> spotlighted the problem in her bestselling `` Silent Spring.'' Most environmentalists have been saying the current bill is better than nothing or, at least, would not make the situation worse. But they point to a lack of any component that would step up monitoring of groundwater, which provides the basic drinking supply for half of all Americans. A report issued last week by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, an organization founded by <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader </PERSON>, said a search of <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> records showed that 73 pesticides have been found in groundwater in 34 states. Moreover, some environmental groups were opposed to the legislation. `` We're not willing to put pesticide regulation on the back burner for three to four years,'' said <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Feldman </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Against </ORGANIZATION> the Misuse of Pesticides. `` That's not any kind of message to be sending out across the country to people who are facing chemicals in their drinking water, chemicals in their workplace and chemicals in their food.''
</TEXT>
