<HEAD>Arizona Newspaper-inspired Probe Gets Additional Money</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> voted Tuesday to appropriate an additional $ 108,000 for the special committee investigating the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> and alleged mismanagement of natural resources such as gas and oil. Last November, the committee unanimously authorized a yearlong, $ 740,000 investigation into alleged fraud, mismanagement and malfeasance in the administration of housing, education and health programs. Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Hawaii </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Indian Affairs, said the investigation `` is the most professional I have seen,'' even more so than the Iran-contra of which he was the co-chairman. He said the special committee headed by Sen. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ariz </LOCATION>., had issued 130 subpoenas and interviewed or taken depositions from over 300 individuals <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON> said there have been allegations of malfeasance, negligence and criminal activity in which the dollar sum may exceed $ 11 billion. <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON> said the special committee would not be rushed in its investigation. He said hearings would be held early in 1989. When the <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON> committee was formed last year, <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON> said the allegations of mismanagement `` extend to almost ever aspect of the administration of <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> affairs, and include the development of Indian trust resources, and the management of housing programs, health programs, education programs, economic development initiatives, and the administration of law enforcement on Indian reservations.'' The special investigation was prompted by a series of articles in The <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> last October. The newspaper reported that multi-million dollar federal Indian programs are plagued by fraud, incompetence and deceit. As an example, <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON> said 34 reports of the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s inspector general and an equal number of reports issued by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the congressional investigative arm, since the early 1970s estimate that the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has failed to collect approximately $ 5.7 billion in oil and gas royalties from oil companies. <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> reports also document another $ 5.8 billion worth of oil and gas that has been illegally siphoned off of Indian and public lands. An <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> account, he said, indicates that the resulting `` windfall to oil companies has been placed at more than $ 1 billion a year in studies by the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s inspector general, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> and congressional panels.''
