<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For the eighth year running, the Oriental Hotel in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, has been rated the world's best hotel in a survey conducted by Institutional Investor magazine. Taking the next three spots were the Regent of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, the Vier Jahreszeiten of <LOCATION> Hamburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, and the Mandarin Oriental of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, all holding the same rankings they had in 1987. The financial monthly magazine polls about 100 senior bankers from around the world who do a lot of traveling and asks them to rate their favorite hotels on a scale of 1 to 100. The top <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hotel was the <PERSON> Carlyle </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, rated No. 12. Five <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hotels were in the top 25. The Connaught of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> moved up to fifth place from eighth last year and the Shangri La of <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> advanced from ninth to sixth. The Okura of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> moved down from sixth to seventh and the <ORGANIZATION> Ritz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paris </ORGANIZATION> fell to eighth from fifth. The Bristol of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, unrated in 1987, took ninth place, and the Peninsula of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> once again held 10th place. The top-ranked Oriental, under German manager <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Wachtveitl </PERSON>, has a staff of 1,000 and has completed a $ 20 million renovation, Institutional Investor says in its September issue. Rounding out the top 25 hotels are: _ Plaza Athenee, <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> _ <PERSON> Carlyle </PERSON>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> _ <PERSON> Claridge </PERSON>'s, <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> _ Dolder Grand,