<FIRST>r w AM-Licenses-Farmers     09-20 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Licenses-Farmers,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmers, Firefighters Need No Special Licenses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday excluded farmers and firefighters from a federal requirement that drivers of large trucks have a special license, saying these groups do not have a poor traffic safety record. The announcement came after several months of public hearings and protests from the farm community over new federal requirements that are aimed at anyone driving a truck weighing more than 26,000 pounds or any vehicles carrying hazardous cargo. Farmers have complained that the special license requirement as enacted by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would cover drivers of large trucks carrying grain and hay, even some pickup trucks, bulk fuel and fertilizer tanks and firefighters driving emergency vehicles. The law provides for the department to allow exemptions. Transportation Secretary <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnley </PERSON> said the states are being notified that they may exempt farm-to-market truck operators as long as the vehicles are used to transport agricultural products, farm machinery or farm supplies no more than 150 miles from home. `` Generally these vehicles have a better accident record than ` non-farm' vehicles of similar size,'' the department concluded. In 1982, the most recent year cited, the accident rate for farm vehicles was less than half the rate for non-farm vehicles, it said. Additionally, the department said, the states may exclude drivers of firefighting equipment operated by municipalities or volunteer fire departments as well as military personnel, including <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guardsmen </ORGANIZATION>, who drive military vehicles. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> enacted the law in 1986 to tighten control over drivers who drive large commercial trucks from state to state. It is aimed at ending the practice by some commercial drivers of obtaining licenses from a number of states to conceal traffic violations. The law also requires minimum standards for commercial drivers and a testing program. Both the licenses and testing continue to be administered by the states. At the same time, the department said it was rejecting requests for similar waivers to transit operators, railroad employees and public utility employees. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON>, R-Mo., principal author of the 1986 law requiring the special licensing, said he agreed with the department's decision `` The law ... was not intended to unduly burden farmers as they transport their grain to the silo or their crops to market,'' <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON> said in a statement.
</TEXT>
