<FIRST>r p AM-Bennett-Dukakis     09-20 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bennett-Dukakis,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bennett, In Last Day As Education Secretary, Bashes Dukakis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Education Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> spent his last day in office Tuesday berating <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and contending <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> advisers `` tend to look down their noses at the basic and instinctive patriotism of a lot of the American people.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> also criticized <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor and Democratic presidential nominee, for vetoing legislation that would have penalized teachers unless they led their students in the Pledge of Allegiance. But in attacking the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> veto, which followed advisory opinions from the state attorney general and supreme court that the bill was unconstitutional, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> also agreed with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> that any student who objects should not be required to recite the pledge. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> supporters turned out in force to greet <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, terming him a hypocrite for criticizing <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> at a time when state spending on education has increased significantly and the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration had tried to cut programs and eliminate the Education Department. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, appearing at a news conference on behalf of Republican presidential nominee <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had at best an average record on education and called his veto of the pledge bill `` his most famous educational act.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said he would oppose such a law at the federal level because education is a state issue. But he said he supported state laws that required the pledge while excusing students who object on religious or other grounds. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> believes recitation of the pledge should be a voluntary tradition in schools, while <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> called for state laws that require recitation but do not penalize students who object. `` If you do n't like the Pledge of Allegiance you're going to hate the Declaration of Independence,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. In a 1986 assessment, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> praised improvements in SAT scores that moved <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> into the top third of states which administer the tests and also credited the state for putting `` in place important reforms to improve teacher quality through testing of new teachers, performance incentives and alternative certifications to attract the most qualified candidates into teaching.'' After being read those comments Tuesday, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said, `` Check the record and see what belongs to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and what belongs to King,'' a reference to former Gov. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. King. When told the teacher-quality legislation was part of a package <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> supported in 1985, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said, `` that may well be ... the governor's record itself is not distinguished.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, during a recent television appearance, said most <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> advisers come from <LOCATION> Brookline </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>, communities where he said many residents have `` disdain'' for patriotism. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, whose tenure was marked by such outspoken and controversial comments, refused to apologize Tuesday but said he was referring specifically to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> advisers. `` A lot of the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> crowd, the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> advisers, do have, I think, a sense of intellectual superiority and do tend to look down their noses at the basic and instinctive patriotism of a lot of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. At the earlier meeting with reporters, <LOCATION> Brookline </LOCATION> state Rep. <PERSON> Eleanor </PERSON> <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON> invited <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> to visit her town, where <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the Democratic presidential nominee, grew up and still lives. `` If Mr. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> thinks <LOCATION> Brookline </LOCATION> disdains basic <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> values, he should visit our town and visit the Civil War, World War I, World War II, Korean War and <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veteran memorials honoring <LOCATION> Brookline </LOCATION> citizens who died to protect his freedom to insult their memory,'' <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON> said.
