<HEAD>Teen's Crow Confiscated And Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>APACHE JUNCTION, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State game officials confiscated and killed a crow that was being kept illegally by a teen-ager who nursed the animal back to health after it lost a wing. <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> law prohibits keeping migratory birds as pets. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Luenz </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 13, was given the bird 2 -LCB- years ago by a neighbor who said vacationers picked it up along the highway after it collided with a tractor-trailer rig. Another family took the bird to a veterinarian, who amputated a mangled wing. <PERSON> Luenz </PERSON> said game warden <PERSON> Dana </PERSON> <PERSON> McGehee </PERSON> told him in July the crow would be confiscated and taken to the state Game and Fish Department sanctuary at Adobe Mountain. `` He told us he would be taken care of out there and that we could go out and see him whenever we wanted to,'' <PERSON> Luenz </PERSON> said. The bird was killed `` because we had no place to put it and it could n't be returned to the wild,'' said <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Spahr </PERSON>, a worker at the Adobe Mountain facility. <PERSON> McGehee </PERSON> was not available for comment Tuesday, but his supervisor said it was unlikely <PERSON> McGehee </PERSON> would have made such a statement. `` We do n't have control over what they do with the animals,'' said <PERSON> McGehee </PERSON>'s supervisor, <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohls </PERSON>. `` I was n't aware it was killed.''
