<HEAD>Anti-Gun Group Says Semiautomatic and Automatic Assault Weapons on
Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The popularity of semiautomatic or automatic assault weapons is increasing dramatically among criminals, especially among those trafficking in illegal drugs, an anti-gun group said Tuesday. The group said police officials across the country are concerned about how frequently criminals are found to possess high-powered automatic assault rifles or shotguns _ some capable of firing 30 rounds in a few seconds. `` The number of assault weapons in civilian hands _ both criminal and law abiding _ is estimated to be in the hundreds of thousands, perhaps millions,'' said a report by the Education Fund to End Handgun Violence, which keeps track of the firearms industry and favors tighter controls over the sale of guns. The group said there are no nationwide statistics available on the misuse of such assault weapons, but that police organizations, government agencies and pro-gun control groups agree the number of such weapons has increased dramatically in recent years. Assault weapons are characterized by having the capability of firing a large number of rounds on a single magazine, great muzzle velocity and compact design often including folding stocks that make it easier for the weapon to be concealed. The assault weapons `` are quickly becoming the leading topic in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s gun control debate and will most likely remain the leading gun control issue for the near future,'' the report said. It said automatic and semiautomatic weapons such as the AR-15, AK-47 and <PERSON> Uzi </PERSON> are among the most popular weapons of drug dealers and are readily available in most states. `` For criminals, the weapons look intimidating, have increased firepower, and can be purchased under the same controls as a hunting rifle or shotgun,'' the report said. It said the weapons are popular not only among criminals, but also survivalists and `` rank-and-file gun aficionados.'' While the group said no national statistics were available on how many such weapons are in circulation, it said in 1987, almost one-third of the weapons seized by the <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> were semiautomatic and 16 percent were fully automatic. Of the 388 guns seized by the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> police department during the first six weeks of this year, `` the vast majority were either semiautomatic or fully automatic,'' the report said. The study was conducted in conjunction with the New Right Watch, a group which monitors right wing organizations.
