<HEAD>No Federal Indictments To Be Sought In 1985 Philadelphia
Confrontation</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf of reax from Philly mayor after 4th graf, It
was</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced Tuesday there is insufficient evidence to seek indictments in the investigation of action taken by <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> city officials and police in the 1985 MOVE confrontation, which left 11 people dead and nearly two square blocks in flames. The investigation examined whether the officials or police violated the civil rights of those who died in the bombing and ensuing fire, said Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON>. `` We ... just found insufficient evidence to go forward with an indictment of anybody,'' <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON>, head of the department's civil rights division, said in an interview. It was the second time a criminal probe of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> <PERSON> Goode </PERSON> and others in connection with the MOVE incident has been concluded without indictments. A local grand jury in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> earlier this year strongly criticized city officials for their handling of the confrontation. Refraining from extensive comment, <PERSON> Goode </PERSON> said he was happy that the investigation was over, adding: `` Two grand juries have fully investigated this matter and have reached a point of no criminality involved. For that I am pleased.'' The local grand jury discounted assertions that police gunfire in an alley behind the MOVE compound kept people from fleeing the burning rowhouse and <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> said the federal probe also had examined that aspect of the matter. In a three-paragraph statement announcing the end of the federal probe, the department said no report will be issued by the fderal grand jury in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> which has been looking into the matter since April 1987. The panel based its inquiry on the work of an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> investigation launched in July 1985. `` It is a very positive thing ... to look forward rather than to look back ... and it really serves no purpose to go back and revisit and re-churn those waters,'' <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> said when asked why the government had decided not to press for a grand jury report on the matter. `` I feel quite strongly that the proper way for a prosecutor to proceed is to make his or her decision,'' announce it and `` nothing -LRB- is -RRB- to be served by any commentary after that.'' <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> praised the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>, said the statements of more than 250 witnesses had been carefully considered and that `` we are satisfied ... there is no basis for a criminal indictment based on our thorough review of all the evidence.'' Five children and six adults died inside the barricaded west <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> rowhouse on May 13, 1985, when police dropped a bomb on the dwelling in an attempt to evict MOVE followers. <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> <PERSON> Goode </PERSON> approved the use of a bomb, which contained the powerful military explosive C-4 and was dropped from a helicopter. The police bomb touched off a rooftop fire that soon raged out of control while fireman held back, afraid they would be hit by gunfire that had echoed through the neighborhood. The fire engulfed almost two square blocks and destroyed 61 rowhouses. Members of the mysterious MOVE group, whose name did not stand for anything in particular, championed back-to-nature rituals, lived in filth, refused to send their children to school, and openly disobeyed health and safety laws. Neighbors had complained to city officials and threatened to take matters into their own hands if nothing was done about MOVE. An investigating commission said the group `` had evolved into an authoritarian, violence-threatening cult.'' <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> District Attorney <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Castille </PERSON> said at the time the local grand jury report came out that it `` laid to rest the MOVE commission's finding and other allegations that police gunfire prevented MOVE members from fleeing the burning compound'' through the back alley. The local grand jury said it considered but discarded charges of conspiracy, murder, involuntary manslaughter, aggravated assault, reckless endangerment, arson, causing or risking a catastrophe, failure to prevent a catastrophe, criminal mischief and perjury. Only two people escaped from the house _ a female MOVE member known as <PERSON> Ramona </PERSON> <PERSON> Africa </PERSON> and then-13-year-old <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Moses </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, known to MOVE members as <PERSON> Birdie </PERSON> <PERSON> Africa </PERSON>. All MOVE members adopted the surname <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and most of them were black. A <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> policeman was killed in a 1978 confrontation with MOVE members.
