<HEAD>Educators Discuss Formation and Propagation of Curriculum on King
Holiday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Educators gathered Tuesday to grapple with the practical and philosophical problems that would confront teachers in developing a kindergarten-12th grade curriculum on the national holiday honoring slain civil rights leader <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> `` If we teach the principles of nonviolent social change to the kids from kindergarten, what do we do when they stage a walkout?'' one educator asked. The answer, from <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> of the Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> Martin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Luther </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> King </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> for Non-Violent Social Change: `` You have to teach them the principles of non-violent social change, let them know that civil disobedience was the last step following long period of negotiation.'' Teaching dilemmas, parental reaction, lack of course materials, training and faculty support were some of the issues raised during the mini-convention on `` Infusing Educational Materials Related to <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, into the Curriculum of the Nation's Schools'' sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holiday </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and the King center Committee members included <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON>; Sister <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON> <PERSON> McNamee </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Manya </PERSON> <PERSON> Ungar </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parents </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Davenport </PERSON>, assistant secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION>, and Mrs. <PERSON> Christine </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Farris </PERSON>, King's sister. Saying she hoped this would be `` the first of many,'' conferences designed to make available audio-visual materials, training programs and other classroom aids, <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> said, `` You can not simply go out and say ` I'm going to teach about the life of Dr. <PERSON> King </PERSON>' unless you know about his life, unless you understand and have resources available.'' <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> said the purpose of the convention was to give the participants an opportunity to come together and `` talk about how we teach about King and how we inculcate that into the curriculum.'' Many of the speakers discussed the problems associated with their particular constituent groups. `` One problem is that no one has ever been really taught about King,'' said <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Ambach </PERSON> of the Council of Chief State School Officers. `` You have to recognize that an association like mine is _ predominantly white, Anglo-Saxon, <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION>, middle class and suburban,'' said <PERSON> Ungar </PERSON> of the national PTA. `` The board members with which I deal ... are not reflective of the greater society _ particularly that portion of society which increasingly has problems getting their voices heard and their agenda addressed,'' she said. She noted that her group was reaching out to other organizations, such as the Anti-Defamation League, to help produce literature by next June. The <ORGANIZATION> PTA </ORGANIZATION> board, which prepared itself through training in human relation skills and a task force for inclusiveness, suggested that the state and local chapters initiate programs which `` demonstrate a commitment to the things that <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> espoused and stood for,'' she said. `` To do this, the parents have got to educate themselves and find out who <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> was,'' <PERSON> Ungar </PERSON> said. `` We hope to have literature aimed at the parents, talking about how we either overtly or covertly teach prejudice, teach racism or perpetuate this cycle of hatred and violence,'' she said.
