<HEAD>Cancer Survivor Becomes Lawyer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man who recovered from a brain tumor and the amputation of his leg following a battle with the cancer that claimed the lives of all his male family members was sworn in to the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> bar Tuesday. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Southerland </PERSON>, 28, stood on one leg and metal crutches, smiling proudly as he recited the oath of admission before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Spellman </PERSON>. `` I am proud to welcome you as a member of the legal fraternity,'' <PERSON> Spellman </PERSON> said, stepping down from the bench to shake the jubilant <PERSON> Southerland </PERSON>'s hand. An apparent genetic defect is responsible for the cancer that has followed the Southerlands for at least four generations, the family's physician, Dr. <PERSON> Beatrice </PERSON> <PERSON> Lampkin </PERSON>, said earlier this year. <PERSON> Southerland </PERSON>'s brother <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> died of leukemia in 1967 at age 4. His father, <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Southerland </PERSON>, 43, died of a brain tumor in 1981, and his brother <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>, 16, died of a rare spinal cancer later that year. The only other family survivor is his mother, <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Southerland-McMillen </PERSON>. <PERSON> Southerland </PERSON> was hopeful he had the cancer beat after his left leg was amputated in 1974. He dreamed of becoming a lawyer and began studying for the bar exam in 1986. Then he suffered a seizure and collapsed during a softball game. Doctors found a golfball-sized malignant brain tumor lodged deep in the left side of his brain and decided to operate. `` It was the best excuse in the world not to take a bar exam,'' he joked at the time. The operation removed any trace of cancer, doctors told him. <PERSON> Southerland </PERSON> began working full time at a <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> law firm and lifting weights three times a week to rega