<FIRST>u i AM-UN-GeneralAssembly 1stLd-Writethru a0717 09-20 0730</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-General Assembly, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0717,0748</SECOND>
<HEAD>Argentine Named Assembly President, Denounces Third World Debt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with new president's speech.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign Minister <PERSON> Dante </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Caputo </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> was elected president of the 43rd General Assembly Tuesday and promptly denounced developed nations for their `` pitiless system'' of piling up Third World debt. <PERSON> Caputo </PERSON> was swiftly elected after the 159-nation world body convened in a mood of optimism and conciliation over many international issues, despite the bitter presidential contest between <PERSON> Caputo </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Barbados </LOCATION>' ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Dame </PERSON> <PERSON> Nita </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrow </PERSON>. In his inaugural speech, <PERSON> Caputo </PERSON> set the tone for his yearlong presidency of the world body which is dominated by poor, developing nations and distanced himself from much of the industrialized West. <PERSON> Caputo </PERSON> cited `` the contrast between political peace and economic injustice ... the widening of the gap between rich countries and a large part of the developing world.'' The 47-year-old former professor and politician was elected by a vote of 91 to 66, with one abstention in secret balloting by 158 nations. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, the 159th member, is disqualified from voting. The abstaining nation was not identified. The post is largely ceremonial but the president has great prestige and can wield considerable influence in setting agendas, limiting speeches and setting the tone for debate. <PERSON> Caputo </PERSON>'s election was a major setback for <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, which lobbied against him and for <PERSON> Dame </PERSON> <PERSON> Nita </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> were foes in the Falklands War of 1982 _ won by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> _ and the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> consistently has taken <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s side. The race was expected to be close, but <PERSON> Caputo </PERSON> won handily over the 71-year-old nurse and public health expert who became the <LOCATION> Barbados </LOCATION> envoy in 1986. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> did not disclose its secret vote. Diplomatic sources said <PERSON> Caputo </PERSON>, who had been courting black <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, won many votes in the non-aligned movement. He also won votes of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and socialist countries; <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>; Arab nations, which need Argentine food, and some European nations which have emigrant ties to <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, the sources said. <PERSON> Caputo </PERSON>, named foreign minister in 1983 by President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>, last month expelled <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s consul for organizing a conference in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> without proper diplomatic clearance. In his speech after Tuesday's election, <PERSON> Caputo </PERSON> praised the improved atmosphere for international cooperation betwen East and West. <PERSON> Caputo </PERSON> cited <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> achievements in the <LOCATION> Iran-Iraq </LOCATION> cease-fire, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> settlement, <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> and other areas. He also denounced the continuing `` infamous practice of apartheid in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>,'' refering to that country's policy of racial segregation. He pointed to the `` sharp deterioration of the situation'' in Israeli-occupied territories. He called for an international peace conference on the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and supported the right of all states in the region to exist within safe boundaries and the right of the Palestinian people to self-determination. But he reserved his strongest comments to condemn the economic gap between the industrialized and the developing world. <PERSON> Caputo </PERSON> noted `` the remarkable difference between all the progress made toward ensuring world peace and the little, or nothing we have done to prevent the widening of the gap between rich countries, and a large part of the developing world.'' He said one of the clearest examples `` of this impotence is the question of the external debt of the developing countries: No structural improvement has taken place for the debtors since the outbreak of the the crisis in 1982.'' The Argentine envoy warned that high interst rates, `` together with the pitiless system of successive refinancing plans, and the perverse outflow of financial resources of indebted countries to credtors will end up eliminatng possibilities of investment for the developing world.'' <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> has a foreign debt of $ 56 billion, the third highest in the developing world. Of the three sources of global conflict _ East-West tension, regional conflicts and the `` unfair relationship between <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> and South'' _ a major <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> effort must be directed toward helping the developing world, <PERSON> Caputo </PERSON> said. He said Northern nations ensured their own wealth by imposing poverty on developing nations, but emphasized that the industrialized nations need the development of other nations to consolidate their own progress. `` They need it,'' he said, `` because development guarantees peace in the Third World and global security and because expansion of trade of developed countries will depend increasingly on growth of economies of the South.''
