<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democratic presidential nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is still unknown to many voters despite more than a year of campaigning, says an <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> poll released Tuesday. The survey, which gave Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> a 50 percent to 46 percent lead over <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, said 54 percent of the respondents thought they did not know enough about <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. That compared with 70 percent who said they think the vice president is a known quantity. The survey of 1,271 likely voters, begun a week ago and concluded Monday, also found that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was favored over <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> among voters who consider themselves independents. The survey had a margin of error of plus or minus three points. The survey also examined which issues were important to voters and how strong they considered each candidate on those issues. According to the survey, six out of ten respondents considered holding down taxes to be a very important issue, and of that group 54 percent thought <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would do a better job while 43 percent thought <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would. Of the two-thirds of the respondents who thought preserving American family values to be a `` cutting edge'' issue, 52 percent supported <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and 44 percent supported <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. But on the issue of creating new jobs, which two-thirds found important, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was favored over <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> 53 percent to 43 percent. Neither candidate led on fighting drugs and crime, holding down the deficit and protecting the environment. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was ahead among voters who were concerned about issues such as the Pledge of Allegiance, the <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATI