<HEAD>Report: At Least 62 Killed In Rebel Rocket Attack in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs with eight grafs to UPDATE with Soviet
report of capture of rebel arsenal; PICKS up 8th pvs: Moslem
guerrillas...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> rebels fired a rocket into <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> on Tuesday that killed at least 62 people and injured 104, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kabul </ORGANIZATION> said. In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, the official Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said two terrorists preparing a bomb for an act of sabotage in another Afghan city were killed when the device exploded. A 9-year-old girl also died in the explosion, it said. `` As a result of the attack -LRB- on <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> -RRB- 62 innocent people, including women and children, were killed and 104 were wounded,'' Radio <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> said in a report monitored in <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION>. It gave few other details. The report tended to reinforce claims by Western sources that U.S.-backed Moslem insurgents have surrounded the heavily-fortified Afghan capital, attacking government and Soviet-held positions. In another report Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kabul </ORGANIZATION> said 10 people were killed when six surface rockets `` launched by extremist opposition elements'' slammed into various parts of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. It was not immediately clear whether the 10 fatalities were included among the 62 reported killed. The report said since the April 14 signing in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> of an accord providing for the withdrawal of Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, anti-communist rebels have rocketed the city 16 times. The 16th attack occurred Tuesday, it said. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> also reported Tuesday that Afghan soldiers captured 14 caches of arms near <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> that contained more than 700 surface-to-air missiles. Afghan soldiers moved into <LOCATION> Lalnadar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gorge </LOCATION>, about 12 miles south of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, after they received intelligence about the arms supplies hidden there, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. Two battalions of Afghan soldiers, supported by Soviet artillery, cut off roads leading out of the gorge, but most of the rebels escaped via mountain paths, it said. `` In all, Afghan troops discovered 14 depots containing 724 surface-to-air missiles, 132 anti-tank and 280 anti-personnel mines, U.S.-made remote-control explosive devices and other weapons,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. Also discovered were submachine guns, grenades, bazookas, and an anti-aircraft gun on a rotating platform, it said. It said the rebels launched missiles at <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> from a nearby mountain ridge, and then scattered because of retaliatory strikes that usually followed. It was not clear if the attack reported by <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> was the same offensive reported Tuesday by Radio <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> also did not say when the weapons were captured from the insurgents, who are seeking to oust the Soviet-backed government of President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> quoted the Afghan news agency <ORGANIZATION> Bakhtar </ORGANIZATION> as saying the accidental bombing occurred in the <LOCATION> Khushkhal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mena </LOCATION> district of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> but did not say when. It did not say whether the terrorists were aligned with anti-communist rebels. Moslem guerrillas have been fighting the ruling communists in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> since they seized power in a 1978 military coup. Soviet forces entered the conflict to back the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government in late 1979. Under this year's <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreement, all of the estimated 100,000 <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> troops are to leave the country by Feb. 15.
