<FIRST>r w AM-IMFMeeting     09-20 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IMF Meeting,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Forsees No Changes in International Economic Policies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The annual gathering of finance ministers and other economic officials at the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> beginning this week in <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> is unlikely to produce a major change in world economic policies, according to a senior <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official. `` The world economy ... is in the best shape that we've seen for a very considerable period of time,'' said the official on Tuesday, adding that American policy will continue steady during President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s final months in office. `` Our principal objectives will be to assure our partners of the continued <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commitment to and support for the economic policy coordination process and the debt strategy,'' said the official. He said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials also would try `` to build on the considerable progress being achieved in promoting a sound world economy and a stable financial system.'' The <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> meeting will be the first opportunity for new <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> to get acquainted with his foreign counterparts, the official noted. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> was confirmed as secretary earlier this month to replace <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, who resigned to head <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s presidential campaign. `` Inflation remains moderate and while continued vigilance is needed on that front, there is no evidence of generalized price pressures emerging,'' the official said. He said `` external imbalances,'' like the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit and the Japanese trade surplus, `` are coming down, more quickly in fact than many people projected, as the latest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures have recently confirmed.'' He said economic growth in the major industrial countries this year will be approximately 4 percent, with continued expansion next year. During the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> meeting, the wealthiest countries, known as the Group of Seven or <ORGANIZATION> G-7 </ORGANIZATION>, plan to review their coordinated approach to the world economy to see if it can be strengthened, the official said. `` We expect the participants of that meeting to reaffirm the policy directions that have been adopted, including the understanding on exchange market cooperation,'' the official said. In recent years the G-7 countries have worked together to lower the value of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar and raise the West German deutsche Mark and Japanese yen on exchange markets. This has lowered the price of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports and made them more competitive in the world market, helping to narrow the difference between what the amount of goods and services the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> exports and imports. The official said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government continues to stand by its approach to easing the Third World debt burden as fundamentally sound and believes `` that significant progress has been and is being achieved.'' The approach, outlined in 1985 by <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, called on commercial banks and international lending agencies to increase loans by $ 29 billion to the poorest 15 countries of the world in exchange for moves by those countries toward free-market economies. Lending by the commercial banks, however, has fallen $ 20 billion short of what the <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> plan envisioned. This has prompted other countries, most notably <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, to suggest alternatives. The official said `` debt-for-equity'' swaps used by some Latin American countries to reduce their indebtedness showed promise. Under the procedure, governments grant commercial banks shares in government-owned businesses in exchange for forgiveness of the government debt to the banks. `` Debt-equity swaps have totaled $ 9 billion dollars by our estimate in the last 18 months or two years,'' said the official. `` There's room for substantially more activity of this kind if various debtor countries would further open their markets and remove foreign-investment restrictions.''
