<HEAD>House Bill Would Allow Federal Agencies' Exit From Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House on Tuesday passed a bill that will allow federal agencies to locate in suburbs outside <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, a move city officials said would mean a substantial loss in local taxes. The bill, which amends a 1959 law requiring that federal agencies be housed in the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, was prompted by concern that federally-leased land within the city had become too expensive. The bill, passed by a voice vote, now goes to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. `` This legislation is important in that it would provide needed flexibility in the location of certain executive agencies in the national capital region at a significant savings to the government,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Average lease rates in the nation's capital range from $ 27 to $ 37 a square foot, compared to only $ 18 to $ 22 per square foot in Prince <PERSON> George </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, and $ 22 to $ 31 per square foot in <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> noted. A recent study by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, the agency which handles all federal land purchases and rental agreements, found that $ 6 million could be saved on a 10-year lease of 100,000 square feet if a federal agency moved to a suburban location. Rep. <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Molinari </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, the bill's chief sponsor, said more than 50 independent agencies would be allowed to relocate outside <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. However, the legislation would not allow the principal offices of the 13 Cabinet-level agencies to move outside the District. `` The fact of the matter is that we have the opportunity in many cases to lease equivalent space nearby in the suburbs at half of what it would cost to stay in the District,'' said <PERSON> Molinari </PERSON>. `` We're not anticipating any large mass-scale exodus, but this could save millions and millions of taxpayer dollars.'' But while the bill could ultimately mean a savings for federal taxpayers, city officials said they will be scrambling to make up for the lost revenue. `` This takes a lot of federal lease space in the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> and sends it out to the suburbs,'' said <PERSON> Julius </PERSON> <PERSON> Hobson </PERSON>, the city's intergovernmental liason officer `` What we will lose is sales tax revenue from federal employees eating and shopping in the city.'' <PERSON> Hobson </PERSON> did not know exactly how much tax revenue the city would lose.
