<HEAD>2nd Blaze In 3 Days Near Subway Station Where 31 Died Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fire in a tunnel Tuesday night delayed subway services at King's Cross station, the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> fire service reported. It was the second fire in the same spot in three days, but no injures were reported in either blaze. On Nov. 18 last year, 31 people died and 80 were injured when fire broke out under an escalator at <ORGANIZATION> King </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> subway system's busiest station. The fire service said in a statement that in Tuesday's incident, trash that had accumulated in the tunnel beween King's <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> and Euston, the next subway station down the line, caught fire but was quickly extinguished. It said that on Saturday, services were briefly disrupted after a small fire broke out at the same spot. That fire burned itself out before emergency crews arrived to tackle it. The statement did not say what was thought to have caused the fires on Tuesday and Saturday. Investigators believe the Nov. 18 fire was started when a lighted cigarette was dropped on a wooden escalator surrounded by grease-soaked trash. The fire raced up the escalator and a ball of flame exploded in the ticket lobby. Smoking has been banned throughout the subway system following the Nov. 18 fire. But an independent inquiry into that fire expressed concern last June at the end of a 91-day hearing that senior managers of <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION>, the public corporation that runs the subway, might not accept the lessons of that disaster. The inquiry's chief counsel, <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON>, accused senior managers of seeking to shirk responsibility for the fire. The managers defended existing safety procedures but during the inquiry announced a package of 101 new safety measures.
