 The case of three men charged in the kidnap-murder of a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> agent slain in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> went to a federal court jury Tuesday. The jury got the case against the trio 3 -LCB- years after the death of <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> agent <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON>, whose battered body was discovered at a ranch in the Mexican countryside. The defendants are alleged to have acted at the behest of Mexican drug baron <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Caro </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON>. Prosecutors contend <PERSON> Caro </PERSON> ordered <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON>'s slaying to wreak vengeance for <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> assaults on his drug empire. Two defendants are charged with kidnap, murder and conspiracy, and one with being an accessory after the fact in the murders of <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> and his pilot. Defense attorneys argued the three are scapegoats of a government intent on closing the books on the politically volatile case, which disrupted relations between the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Jurors who heard eight weeks of testimony were instructed by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafeedie </PERSON>, then received the case. They selected a foreman then retired until Wednesday to begin deliberating. Earlier in the day, a prosecutor delivered his final statement, denouncing defense lawyers for `` outrageous and obscene'' arguments. He called for conviction of all defendants. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Roel </PERSON> <PERSON> Campos </PERSON>, in a rebuttal that drew a barrage of objections from the defense and an unsuccessful motion for mistrial, said the lawyers had stooped to unwarranted personal attacks on the prosecution te