<HEAD>Government Outlines Laws To Seize Terrorist Funds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLACKPOOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government outlined sweeping legislation Tuesday to prevent funds reaching terrorists, including new police powers and a change in bank secrecy laws. Home Secretary <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> unveiled the proposals at a police conference in this northwest resort town. The measures will come before Parliament next year. Police welcomed them, but civil libertarians expressed some concern. `` The time has come for firm action to throttle the flow of cash to terrorist organizations,'' <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> said. He said the laws include outlawing handling funds for terrorists, freezing or confiscating these funds and freeing banks from secrecy rules so they can inform police of suspect deposits. `` We shall draw the definition of ` terrorist purposes' wide enough to catch anyone connected with this trade of death,'' <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> said. Police `` will be able to seek warrants to get at relevant material, including bank records of transactions,'' he said. The laws would bar handling assets that are `` to be used for terrorist purposes, even if that activity is going on in an otherwise legitimate business,'' <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> said. A court convicting a person could `` confiscate any property or money that he has handled and that is intended for use in terrorist acts or in connection with terrorism,'' <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> said, adding the court would assume the money was tainted `` unless someone with an interest in it could show otherwise.'' Anticipating criticism, <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> said while democracies `` need to consider long and hard'' before adopting such measures, `` our conclusion is that the police and the courts must no longer lack the necessary powers to find and cut off the fuel which sustains the engines of murder.'' The proposals were seen mainly as a weapon against the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, which is fighting to rid <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> of British rule and unite the Protestant-dominated province with the 95-percent Catholic Irish Republic. <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON>, general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION>, objected to making the defendant prove funds were not destined for terrorist activity, saying: `` In many cases this could prove an impossible task.'' <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, a senior <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> police official, welcomed the proposals. `` If we can stop the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>'s money at source we can help prevent them buying arms and explosives,'' he said. `` No organization can last without funds.'' Protestant Rev. <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unionist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said the measures were `` too little, too late.'' He said the restrictions could be dodged by funneling the money to the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>'s legal political wing, <ORGANIZATION> Sinn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fein </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> claims one source for the estimated $ 8.5 million reaching <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> coffers annually is <LOCATION> Noraid </LOCATION>, a pro-IRA fund-raising group in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> did not spell out whether the new laws would affect <LOCATION> Noraid </LOCATION> contributions, but said bilateral agreements would be sought with foreign governments to help seize suspect funds.
