<HEAD>Tropical Storm Helene Forms in Eastern Atlantic</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with potential for hurricane development,
new location, wind speed, quotes</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tropical Storm <PERSON> Helene </PERSON> formed in the eastern <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> on Tuesday and showed potential for strengthening into a hurricane in the next day or two, the National Hurricane Center reported. <PERSON> Helene </PERSON> is the eighth named storm of the 1988 <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> hurricane season and the first since Hurricane Gilbert formed in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> and went on to ravage <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Helene </PERSON>'s winds, based on satellite photos, reached 60 mph Tuesday and was moving west at about 15 mph, according an advisory from the hurricane center. Meteorologist <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lascody </PERSON> said a storm path can not be projected until it moves closer to the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>. `` It's going across the warmest water of the year now, which is perfect to fuel its growth,'' <PERSON> Lascody </PERSON> said Tuesday night. `` But it really would be very premature to give a guess on what may happen. It still has a long way to go.'' Storms that form this month near the <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Verde </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> off <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s coast are often the season's strongest because of ideal hurricane-spawning conditions, forecasters say. Factors such as low-pressure zones in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> and high-level winds will affect the path of the storm, said <PERSON> Lascody </PERSON>. `` It looks like it will reach its make-or-break point sometime later this week,'' he said. The depression that became <PERSON> Helene </PERSON> had initially seemed disorganized, but satellite photos showed circulation had improved. The hurricane center has not yet received ship reports on the storm's intensity. At 10:30 p.m. EDT, <PERSON> Helene </PERSON>'s center was located 1,500 miles east of the <LOCATION> Lesser </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antilles </LOCATION> at latitude 12 north, longitude 37.8 west. It will take about four days for <PERSON> Helene </PERSON> to get close enough to the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> to allow an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> reconnaissance plane to overfly the storm. Until then, hurricane forecasters will have to rely on satellite reports, said forecaster <PERSON> Miles </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON>. He emphasized there was no way to tell if <PERSON> Helene </PERSON> would become as powerful as the deadly <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>, which forecasters have called the storm of the century. <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>, which had winds about 175 mph at its peak, did not reach tropical storm strength until reaching the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>.
