<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New studies show breast cancer deaths can be reduced by 24 percent among women aged 40 to 49 if they have mammogram examinations every one to two years, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. <ORGANIZATION> NCI </ORGANIZATION> scientists said a new analysis of data from a clinical trial conducted by the Health Insurance Plan of Greater <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> confirms that there are definite life-saving benefits for mammographic screening among 40-to-49-year-old women. `` This is the first statistically significant evidence of the benefits'' for this age group, said <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Chu </PERSON>, lead author of the <ORGANIZATION> NCI </ORGANIZATION> analysis.
