<HEAD>Fires Bring Emotional Reactions From Yellowstone Neighbors</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Yellowstone Recovery</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Falacy </PERSON> saw open flames near the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cascade </LOCATION> in fire-ravaged <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> recently, he stopped his truck, ran into the blackened woods with a shovel and attacked the hot spots. `` I'm from <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and I wo n't let it burn anymore,'' said <PERSON> Falacy </PERSON>, who grew up in <LOCATION> Missoula </LOCATION> and lives in <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>, N.M. He should n't have done it, because he had no firefighting gear or protective clothing and because snags are dangerous, but his wife, <PERSON> Becky </PERSON>, said she could n't stop him. `` He's really upset,'' she said. The Falacys were in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> to check out the damage from the worst forest fires in centuries. Nearly half the park's 2.2 million acres have been charred by wildfires this summer. `` It was about what I expected, but <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> just could n't take it when he saw the flames,'' <PERSON> Becky </PERSON> <PERSON> Falacy </PERSON> said. `` He saw flames and went right down there. You could n't stop him.'' <PERSON> Falacy </PERSON>'s typified the reactions of people from the <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> neighborhood _ the states of <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>. `` I did n't realize how much damage there is until we saw it for ourselves,'' said <PERSON> Bonnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Townsend </PERSON>, of <PERSON> Bozeman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mont </PERSON>. `` It was bad enough reading about it. This is so awful I ca n't describe it.'' Living near the nation's oldest national park generates a proprietary interest in its welfare, and there is much anger over the events of the summer. However, tourists from distant parts of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and overseas are less emotional about the damage and say they expected to see far worse. `` When it all grows back it will be twice as pretty,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Quiggle </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Huntington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Quiggle </PERSON> said television coverage of the fires had led him to believe that `` all I'd see was burned trees They made it sound like the whole park was scorched to the ground.'' Forest fires burn in a scattered pattern called a mosaic by foresters. Acres of blackened trees are interspersed with untouched stands. Other sections are burned at ground level, but foliage is untouched. Many of the park's most popular attractions have escaped the fires. No damage is visible at the falls near <LOCATION> Canyon </LOCATION>, Artist Point and the north shore of <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>. Old Faithful, however, is partially surrounded by scorched trees. A tour group from <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> marveled at the parts of the park that remain _ at least so far _ undamaged. `` We thought it might be worse,'' said <PERSON> Val </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellerington </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Cokedale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION>. `` But it's a beautiful place. `` We've been able to see the falls and Old Faithful and what we wanted to see, and we're so glad we could see <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> at all,'' she said. <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> and <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, said they, too, expected more damage. Gazing out over the spectacular canyon and the falls of the <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said she hated to see the burned trees visible from some roads, but was n't disappointed with the park. `` The main reason to come to the park is the things like Old Faithful, the canyon, animals and geysers, and all these things are here,'' she said. `` There's a lot left.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 25</NOTE>
