<FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 1335EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s p BC-DebatingtheIssues ADV25-1stAdd   09-20 0948</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Debating the Issues, ADV 25-1st Add,0969</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<BYLINE>WASHINGTON: donor banks.
   ^ENVIRONMENT</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> says, `` In the past few years, we have not done enough to protect the environment. I will do more.'' He promises to seek an end to ocean dumping of wastes by 1991, a goal of `` no net loss of wetlands'' and a moratorium on offshore oil drilling in sensitive areas such as the <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> coast. He also says he will seek to curb acid rain by finding ways to cut `` millions of tons of sulfur dioxide emissions by the year 2000 and to significantly reduce nitrogen oxide emissions,'' and to accelerate the Superfund cleanup of toxic wastes. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> says he will set and enforce strict standards for air and water quality and strengthen the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> to `` make the polluters pay.'' He says he will work with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> `` to stop the acid rain pollution of North American skies and waters.'' He promises to `` halt below-cost timber sales in national forests'' and he opposes offshore drilling in environmentally sensitive areas, including the <ORGANIZATION> Georges </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> off <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DRUGS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> calls drugs `` a cancer on our society'' and says he will make his running mate, Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, czar of an administration-wide assault on drugs. `` We have had some good results in stopping this poison at the borders. But drug abuse must be attacked not only by stopping the supply, but also by stopping the demand,'' says <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` We have to educate our children about the dangers of drugs.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> says he will wage `` a real war, not a phony war, against drugs.'' He promises to appoint a federal czar to oversee the nation's drug enforcement, rehabilitation and education efforts. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> vows to cut off foreign aid to governments that refuse to cooperate with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> efforts, hire 600 more <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> agents and strengthen the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, and dispatch the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military `` under appropriate circumstances'' to help foreign governments eradicate drug crops and drug processing labs. He promises to expand aid for drug treatment clinics to make space available for any addict who wants to kick the habit.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ENERGY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, a former oilman, has proposed a 10 percent tax credit for oil and gas exploration. He wants to fully decontrol natural gas prices, use more coal as an energy source and fill up the <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> faster. He says nuclear power `` must be a part of our energy mix.'' He opposes an oil import fee. He says, `` There is no way to meet our energy requirements without offshore drilling,'' but some sensitive tracts should not be leased. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> opposes the construction of new commercial nuclear reactors until new reactors are designed and safe ways are found to treat and dispose of radioactive wastes. He also would fill the <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>. He says the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must become less dependent on imported oil. `` We must use cleaner fuels, like natural gas, and better technologies, like clean coal. And we must promote alternatives to fossil fuels and significantly increase energy efficiency and conservation,'' he says. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, too, opposes an oil import fee.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>EDUCATION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Each candidate says he wants to be `` the education president.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has promised to spend more on Head Start, the preschool program for needy children, and to increase the education budget by $ 600 million, including a new `` Merit Schools'' program that would reward schools that make strides in educating the disadvantaged. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also has proposed allowing parents to earn interest tax-free on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> savings bonds. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has said he favors creating a $ 250 million National Teaching Excellence Fund to attract people to teaching with scholarships, sabbaticals and other incentives. He says he is committed to the principle that no qualified student should be denied a college education because of financial need. He has proposed allowing students to borrow money for college and pay it back through a payroll withholding tax throughout their working lives. He promises to work in partnership with the private sector to eliminate adult illiteracy.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HEALTH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> says, `` We must mount a comprehensive effort to reduce the cost and improve the quality of, and access to, health care in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' He says Medicare may be able to save money by extending its prospective payment system for hospitals to physician and outpatient services, but he is wary of `` regulatory schemes that could have the unintended effect of lowering the quality of health care.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> favors tax incentives to encourage people to save for their own long-term costs in nursing homes. He says elderly couples should not have to bankrupt themselves before qualifying for government help. The centerpiece of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' health program is a promise to make basic health insurance available to all American workers, with their employers footing the bill. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> recently became the first state to impose such a requirement on all but the smallest employers. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> maintains this can be done at no cost to the federal government. Business groups contend it would cost employers heavily and result in job losses. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> says he also is committed to the goal of ensuring that all the elderly have access to long-term care. `` With a $ 150 billion federal budget deficit, we will not realize this goal overnight. But we must begin now, with commitment and compassion,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> says.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CAPITAL PUNISHMENT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> suports the death penalty `` for crimes involving murder, treason or espionage,'' as well as for narcotics kingpins. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> opposes capital punishment under any circumstances.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SCHOOL PRAYER</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> supports organized, voluntary prayer in public schools `` as an extension of our commitment to teaching values.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> opposes prayer in public schools.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 25</NOTE>
