<HEAD>Energy Futures Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More bad news about an oversupply of oil on world markets overshadowed a mixed performance in energy futures. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the October contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, settled 16 cents higher at $ 14.73 a barrel Monday after a late-afternoon rally in anticipation of the contract's expiration on Tuesday. Wholesale unleaded gasoline for October delivery gained 0.02 cent to close at 44.24 cents a gallon. The October wholesale heating oil contract lost 0.01 cent to settle at 41.36 cents a gallon. Analysts said the market opened lower, influenced by a report that <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> intentionally was violating its production quota in a direct challenge to the 12 other nations of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries. The Petroleum Intelligence Weekly, a respected industry newsletter, said the quota violation was a <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> strategy ahead of next week's meeting of the cartel's price monitoring committee to bring other quota violators back in line with <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> pricing policy by competing with them for market share. The meeting is scheduled for Sept. 25 and 26, either in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> or on the <LOCATION> Indonesian </LOCATION> island of <LOCATION> Bali </LOCATION>, according to reports. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> is <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s largest oil producer and once was considered the swing producer, and in a position to influence other <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members. But recently, some analysts have questioned <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s leadership role. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, for example, has refused to abide by an OPEC-imposed quota, saying it needs the oil revenue to rebuild its war-torn country. Other member nations also have admitted violating output limits. Analysts said the market interpreted the Saudi report negatively. They said last week's optimism that an <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> price meeting could lead to production limits and higher oil prices has now turned mixed. Analysts also said Monday that gasoline futures were surprisingly weak after last week's rally brought on by the threat of a hurricane disrupting production in the Gulf of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. `` I guess it was an overbought market,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kane </PERSON>, an oil broker with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
