<SECOND>PM-World Bank-IMF, Bjt,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Of Seven To Meet Prior To Annual World Bank-IMF Gathering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 World finance officials begin arriving this week for the annual World Bank-International Monetary Fund meeting, which is expected to be more a forum for discussion of economic ailments than a producer of any historic policy decisions. Finance ministers, central bankers and other officials from 151 countries are expected to attend the joint meeting, the first ever held in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Representatives of the countries will present their nations' positions on various economic issues at a plenary session scheduled for Sept. 27-29 Preliminary talks that include a meeting of officials of the world's seven largest industrial democracies _ the so-called <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seven </ORGANIZATION> _ begin Thursday. Coincidentally, Thursday is the three-year anniversary of the so-called Plaza Agreement in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, in which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> agreed to depress the dollar's foreign exchange value to help curb the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit. Since then, the dollar has declined by nearly 45 percent against the Japanese yen, a move cited as a key factor in cutting the deficit over that time. Also during the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> discussions, the G-7 nations are slated to review their economic coordination policies. The Group of Seven comprises the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. Observers say the Group of Seven likely will reaffirm its intention to keep the dollar steady at around current levels and restate its belief that an excessive rise or fall of the dollar would be counterproductive to world economies. <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> officials and private economists say the importance of the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> meeting is not its results, but the new ideas it produces. `` I do n't think there will be any major decisions, but there should be a lively exchange of new ideas,'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Pietsch </PERSON>, economist for the <ORGANIZATION> Commerzbank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, said in an interview. <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartmann </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, told reporters last week: `` We expect no historical decisions.'' Also scheduled to meet this week on Thursday are deputy finance ministers of the Group of 24 developing countries. The plight of heavily indebted developing nations is expected to be a major topic during the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> talks. According to <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> annual report released Sept. 14, the industrial nations are in good financial health but the overall situation among developing countries remains far from satisfactory. The <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> report said total debt of the developing countries increased 10.4 percent in 1987 from the previous year to $ 1.2 trillion, while their average growth rage fell to 3.4 percent in 1987 from 4.2 percent in 1986. The Third World debt issue likely will be dramatized in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> by protests expected to be staged concurrently with the finance meetings. About 40,000 protesters have said they will come to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> to denounce what they see as unfair treatment of the developing nations by richer industrialized lands and calling for general Third World debt relief, according to organizers. Industrialized nations and private banks have been encouraging developing countries to undertake economic reform in exchange for help with their debts. <PERSON> Pietsch </PERSON>, the West German economist, says that strategy continues to show the most promise. However, some indebted nations have called for more sweeping solutions to their problem, including partial or whole debt forgiveness. `` A general debt relief would not help to stabilize economies and societies,'' <PERSON> Pietsch </PERSON> said. `` We need to be flexible and look for new instruments -LRB- to help reduce developing countries' debts -RRB-. The debt countries are also creating lots of innovations in order to overcome their problems,'' he said. French Economics Minister <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Beregovoy </PERSON> has indicated that during the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> discussions he plans to unveil a proposal aimed at encouraging banks to step up their lending to middle-income debtors. Other topics likely to be discussed during the meeting are the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade and budget deficits, protectionism and high inflation in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, represented by its newly appointed <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, is expected to stress that the next <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> president would continue the nation's cooperation with the rest of the G-7 countries. There also could be discussion of a possible Soviet entry in the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s minister for economic cooperation, said last week he would be `` extremely happy'' with such a move, which he said likely would speed up structural economic reform within the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.
