<FIRST>r f PM-BabyBag Bjt   09-20 0819</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baby Bag, Bjt,0845</SECOND>
<HEAD>Entrepreneur Warmed By Baby Bag Profits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEN O'QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CUMBERLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Its inventor says the Baby Bag was born of desperation. In years past, <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> would have to grit her teeth and try stuffing her 4-month-old daughter <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> into a snowsuit while the child twisted, kicked and screamed until her veins bulged. Bundled and ready, <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> needed a diaper change; once outdoors, her mittens fell off, creating another trauma. This was no way to enjoy winter, <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> thought. Some type of bag-like outfit would be more convenient and more protective of the baby's face. So <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> stitched together a cozy little bunting sack to replace the traditional snowsuit, called it Baby Bag and began selling the insulated outfit in stores. It was an immediate success. `` It's a good product to sell because it's a very simple design, and the -LRB- promotional -RRB- pictures are always cute because the babies are cute,'' <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> said during a recent interview at her office in this <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> suburb. In 1980 _ a year after she began selling the bunting suits _ Andrews and husband <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellison </PERSON> formed <ORGANIZATION> Baby </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bag </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. They sold 681 bags that winter. The company now sells more than 30,000 bags a year and has recorded annual revenue over $ 500,000. <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> also has expanded the company's facilities in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, expanded her product line, added a manufacturer in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> and begun to set up marketing in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The bag _ which retails for $ 30 to $ 40 _ is displayed in several catalogs nationwide and sells in about 800 stores in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. It has been written up in Good Housekeeping and Parents magazines, and was displayed among several new consumer products on <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Good Morning America'' program. Using the bag is relatively easy. Parents can slide a child in and out of the bag without the pushing and pulling associated with tight-fitting snowsuits. The baby is warmed by its own body heat, which rises from the bottom of the bag. Loosening the strings at the top of the suit provides ventilation without having to undress a baby, as with traditional snowsuits. <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON>, 39, says the outfit was born of desperation. Just the sight of a snowsuit coming out of the closet sent her daughter into a 15-minute tantrum. `` I needed something to pop her in and get outside quickly because once she was outside she was fine,'' <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON>' sewing experience was limited to repairing a few sails on the sloop she and her husband operated as a charter boat. Undaunted, she stitched a prototype one-piece suit that drew favorable comments from people who noticed the curious attire. She hired a Camden tent company to make the bags she distributed to friends, who encouraged her and her husband to open a business. They patented the bag and tried to persuade the outdoor outfitter L.L. Bean, based in nearby <ORGANIZATION> Freeport </ORGANIZATION>, to buy their idea and manufacture the product. But the company turned them down, saying <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> and her husband should develop the product themselves. With a few magazine advertisements, a $ 5,000 bank loan and 500 baby bags manufactured by a local sportswear company, the couple began a mail-order business at home in 1980. Telephone orders poured in day and night from around the country. Soon after, a product buyer at L.L. Bean helped <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> improve her idea, and the outfitter finally agreed to carry the bag in a December 1983 mail-order catalog. The backing from L.L Bean, coupled with a few magazine ads and displays at trade shows, pushed annual sales to $ 350,000 by the spring of 1984. While her business succeeded, <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON>' marriage fell apart. She sold the mail-order division to another <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> company, Good Gear For Little People, but was frightened by the prospect of managing a wholesale business alone. `` I was a child of the 60's who never thought I would ever have to be serious about anything,'' she said. `` I had never been a person with a purpose or a goal.'' The warm and cheerful <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> says she adopted a slightly sharper edge following her divorce, quickly realizing that companies took her product more seriously once they saw she was assertive and persistent. Last year, she moved the business to <LOCATION> Cumberland </LOCATION>, where she lives with <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON>, now 10, and her second husband, <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Krill </PERSON>. They renovated their barn into offices where <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON>, dressed in jeans and running shoes, scurries around with her three employees managing a line of products that now includes mittens, booties, snowcuffs for ankles, hooded jackets and pants. The products are made in <LOCATION> Fryeburg </LOCATION> by stitchers for a sportswear company who work part-time for <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON>. They can produce about 7,000 Baby Bags a month and thousands of the other accessories. <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> chuckles at her success, calling it `` a real story about how people who do n't know anything about anything can do something.''
</TEXT>
