<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-GNP     09-20 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-GNP,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's GNP Declines In Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s economy contracted during the second quarter due mainly to lower demand for exports and declining investment in private housing, the government reported Tuesday. Overall economic growth, as measured by the gross national product, declined at an annual rate of 3.9 percent during the April to June period, the <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said. On an adjusted basis, the GNP fell by 1 percent, the agency said. During the first quarter, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s GNP grew 2.7 percent, or at an annual rate of 11.3 percent, according to the government report. The decline in the total value of goods and services produced in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> during the period was the first quarter-on-quarter contraction in the country's economy since the January to March 1986 period, when the economy briefly declined under the impact of the sharply rising yen. The government's GNP growth rate target for the current fiscal year is 3.8 percent. Agency officials said a 1.5 percent decline in foreign demand for Japanese products and services and a downturn in private housing investment over the previous quarter's levels more than offset a modest growth in domestic personal consumption and private capital investment. The greatest declines were in the yen value of exports of televisions, video tape recorders, radios and motor vehicles, they said. The Japanese yen has risen by about 83 percent against the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar in the past three years, making Japanese products more expensive overseas. But despite the downturn from healthy GNP growth levels in previous months, agency officials said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s economy remained fundamentally strong. `` It's still showing a positive progression overall,'' said one official, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` There's no reason to think that Japanese economic expansion has ended,'' said <PERSON> Kenji </PERSON> <PERSON> Ito </PERSON>, senior economist for the <ORGANIZATION> Industrial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION>. `` The fall in housing investments is a little steeper than expected, but on the whole we thought the numbers would be in this range.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> had predicted earlier that the second quarter's GNP would remain unchanged or decline slightly from the previous quarter after statistics showed housing starts in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> were peaking. Housing construction had boomed because of low interest rates and huge government expenditures in public works, which indirectly stimulated construction and other industries.
</TEXT>
