graf, `Under the ....'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This city approved a tentative $ 6.5 million settlement in the massive <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Public Power Supply System lawsuit, leaving 18 defendants on trial over a record $ 2.25 billion bond default. `` I feel fantastic, very relieved,'' Councilman <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> <PERSON> Bray </PERSON> said after the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> approved the settlement Monday as the federal trial continued in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz </LOCATION>. Plaintiffs in the case, including more than 24,000 bond buyers, sued over <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION>' 1983 bond default, which came after it abandoned two nuclear power plants under construction. The default was the biggest ever in the municipal bond market. Under the settlement, which is subject to approval by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Browning </PERSON>, <PERSON> Richland </PERSON> will pay <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> bondholders $ 6.5 million, of which $ 3.725 million will be paid by <ORGANIZATION> Twin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The remaining $ 2.775 million comes from 1982 bonds Richland sold to cover WPPSS plant termination costs and some capital improvements, said City Manager <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> <PERSON> Shulman </PERSON>. The bond issue was factored into past city electric rate hikes, <PERSON> Shulman </PERSON> said. The city also agreed to testify on bondholders' behalf. <LOCATION> Richland </LOCATION>, which has more than 30,000 residents, had a 1.965 percent interest in the scrapped nuclear plant projects. The settlement leaves 15 public utilities, two engineering firms and a financial company as defendants in the trial, which was moved to <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> because of pretrial publicity. Seven other utilities settled with the plaintiffs before the trial began earlier this month. Defendants argued in opening statements Monday that a 1983 <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling was to blame for the default. The high court invalidated agreements that 88 utilities signed to participate in building the nuclear plants financed by the bonds. `` The cause of the loss here is almost like an act of God, an act of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nickerson </PERSON>, attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Klickitat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utility </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION>. The ruling stemmed from a lawsuit by some utilities questioning the agreements' validity. By nullifying them, the court removed the guarantee that the bonds would be paid even if the plants were never built. Although the ruling applied to them, none of the utilities was part of that lawsuit. In opening arguments last week, bondholders' attorneys said the defendants lied about power needs in the <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION>, rising costs and construction delays. They contended that if the truth had been told, the bond would not have gone on the market. Defense attorneys argued Monday that their clients revealed all the information they were supposed to provide and did their best to estimate costs and construction schedules. `` The evidence will show that these official statements were as complete and accurate as people could make them, and they were not filled with misstatements,'' said attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagan </PERSON>, representing financial consultant <ORGANIZATION> Blyth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Webber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Hagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nickerson </PERSON> said public utility commissioners and <PERSON> Blyth </PERSON> employees were so confident in the information that they also bought bonds Testimony is scheduled to begin Thursday after a two-day recess. <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> was formed by public utilities to build and operate major electric plants in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>.
