<FIRST>a f BC-WhiteWheat Adv24-25   09-20 0782</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-White Wheat, Adv 24-25,0806</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 24</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Sept. 24-25 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Growing White Wheat In a Field of Red</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The prospect of naturally sweeter bread and new export markets is sparking fresh interest in the cultivation of hard white winter wheat in the Plains states. While the hard red variety has been king of the Plains for more than a century, a number of growers in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> are now giving white a try. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wheat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which sprang from a group organized in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, the nation's No. 1 wheat-producing state, says millers may pay premium prices for white wheat because it yields more flour per bushel. White also has bread baking qualities comparable to hard red, long the world's premium bread wheat. Because of its lighter kernel color _ amber rather than the red _ more of the white wheat kernel can be ground and the flour is lighter in color than that of red wheat, said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Keesling </PERSON>, president of the producers' group. The white wheat flour also has a slightly sweeter taste because the kernels lack the tannins that give red wheat bran a bitter taste, <PERSON> Keesling </PERSON> said. Thus, bakers can save money by cutting down on sweetners normally used to offset the slight bitterness of red wheat flour. `` My wife bakes with whole wheat flour from white wheat sometimes and people think the things taste sweeter, even though the sugar in the recipe actually is reduced,'' said <PERSON> Keesling </PERSON>, a Chase, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, farmer. Hard red wheat has been the favorite among <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> growers because it had the advantage of catching on first, after <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> immigrants introduced it to the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>. As a result, little hard white wheat is now grown in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Some is raised in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, and researchers in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> are experimenting with hard white varieties. Most of the white wheat cultivated in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is of the soft variety, grown primarily in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> and used in cookie and biscuit products. The movement to hard white is small but organized. The new producers' group is incorporated as a marketing cooperative, which controls the sale of the members' white wheat, said <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Tice </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wheat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Growers </ORGANIZATION>. The white wheat will be treated as a specialty crop and separated from hard red for marketing and storage. To avoid mixing it with other varieties on the open market, the white wheat will be sold on a contract basis by the cooperative. <PERSON> Keesling </PERSON> expects <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> growers to plant more than 2,000 acres of hard white wheat this fall, mostly in the western part of the state, where growing conditions are best. Moister conditions in the east have caused the hard white wheat to exhibit `` head sprouting'' _ in which the kernels in the heads of the plants begin to sprout, destroying the value of the grain for milling purposes. <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> wheat breeders are working on a new variety with resistance to sprouting, but it is several years down the road. One <ORGANIZATION> KSU </ORGANIZATION> variety being tested this year may be released in 1989, said <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> KSU </ORGANIZATION> wheat breeder stationed at the Fort Hays Experiment Station. <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Feltner </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> KSU </ORGANIZATION> associate agriculture dean and director of agriculture experiment stations, said increased grower interest has given a dramatic boost to white wheat research begun in the late 1950s. `` Within the past 18 months or so the administration has given us the green light to go ahead and increase our efforts because of the extraction rate and possible marketing niches -LRB- for white wheat -RRB-'' <PERSON> Feltner </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> KTECH </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a state economic development agency, gave the university a $ 160,000 grant that was matched with $ 160,000 from the <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wheat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to work on white wheat and other wheat projects. <PERSON> Feltner </PERSON> said grain scientists are studying white wheat quality and end uses and agricultural economists are studying its market potential. One of the areas being evaluated is white wheat's export promise. Many of the world's importing countries prefer white wheat, said <ORGANIZATION> KSU </ORGANIZATION> breeder <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>. `` Hopefully, this would open up some new avenues in some traditionally Australian white wheat markets,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said. Australian white has been a favorite in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exporters would likely target some of those strongholds. `` I think we're probably a couple of years away from knowing whether white wheat is going to have an exciting start in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> or whether it's going to be a gradual transition,'' said <PERSON> Feltner </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Sept. 24-25</NOTE>
