<HEAD>Scallen: A `Mini-Disney' Pumps Life Into Ice Capades,
Globetrotters</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leave it to show business veteran <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Scallen </PERSON> to team the forces of Olympic silver medal figure skater <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Manley </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Harlem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globetrotters </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s superstar on ice wo n't suit up with the magicians of basketball, but she is performing under the same flag: <PERSON> Scallen </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Scallen </PERSON>'s company purchased the <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Calif.-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globetrotters </ORGANIZATION> and Ice Capades for $ 30 million in December 1986 from <ORGANIZATION> Metromedia </ORGANIZATION> Signing <PERSON> Manley </PERSON> to the Ice Capade's fall tour is one of many moves the former public defender, banker and motion picture executive has made to revitalize the skating troupe. He also has added a second squad to the <ORGANIZATION> Globetrotters </ORGANIZATION> and hired female players <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodge </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lieberman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> to draw more women to the games. What's more, <PERSON> Scallen </PERSON> recently acquired the <LOCATION> Boblo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> amusement park near <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> for $ 19.5 million. He says the 272-acre island in the lower <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> will generate cash flow during the summer months when the <ORGANIZATION> Globetrotters </ORGANIZATION> and Ice Capades are idle. `` What we are is a mini-Walt Disney,'' said the 62-year-old Scallen. `` We want to expand within the concept of quality family entertainment.'' Besides the Ice Capades, <ORGANIZATION> Globetrotters </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Boblo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Scallen </PERSON>'s company owns a controlling interest in <ORGANIZATION> Century </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> production company that made the movie `` Shoot to Kill,'' starring <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Poitier </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Berenger </PERSON>. A second film, `` South of <PERSON> Picasso </PERSON>,'' is in the works and will feature <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanks </PERSON>. <PERSON> Scallen </PERSON> also has his eyes on more regional amusement parks and some television stations. It was <PERSON> Scallen </PERSON>'s sale of Big Country TV of <LOCATION> Abilene </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, for an after-tax profit of $ 4.9 million that allowed him to purchase the Ice Capades and <ORGANIZATION> Globetrotters </ORGANIZATION>. `` Let's say <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kluge </PERSON> -LRB- chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Metromedia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- and <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> are my role models,'' <PERSON> Scallen </PERSON> said. So far, <PERSON> Scallen </PERSON> has transformed <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> from an obscure penny stock company, which lost $ 1.2 million on sales of $ 2 million in 1986, to a $ 34 million company that expects to post net earnings this year of more than $ 2 million. <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> stock now trades in the range of $ 10 a share on the national over-the-counter market. The business seems to fit <PERSON> Scallen </PERSON>'s colorful past. There was the law degree from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Denver </ORGANIZATION> that allowed him to work in that city as a public defender before returning to his hometown of <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, where he acquired his love of skating. He said he returned to <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> to join a law firm in which his father was a partner. From there he turned to a banking career, starting the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minneapolis </ORGANIZATION> and helping to finance <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Robbie </PERSON>'s purchase of the <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dolphins </ORGANIZATION> professional football team. But he quit that to launch his show business career that eventually had him running Shipsteads & amp; Johnson Ice Follies, Holiday on Ice, and the <PERSON> Clyde </PERSON> <PERSON> Beatty-Cole </PERSON> <PERSON> Bros </PERSON>. Circus. He also worked briefly in a top executive post at 20th Century Fox. His darting moves through the entertainment world were briefly derailed in the early 1980s when <PERSON> Scallen </PERSON> ran afoul of Canadian securities laws. He was convicted _ but later pardoned _ for distributing a false prospectus on a loan he arranged to help finance his acquisition of the <ORGANIZATION> Vancouver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canucks </ORGANIZATION> hockey team. In typical style, <PERSON> Scallen </PERSON> emerged from the episode relatively unscathed. He was paroled after serving nine months of a two-year prison sentence and was pardoned in 1982 by the solicitor general of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Later, he even sold the <ORGANIZATION> Canucks </ORGANIZATION> for a profit, he says. `` There's no way of telling how painful an experience like that -LRB- prison term -RRB- was,'' <PERSON> Scallen </PERSON> said after receiving the pardon. `` Particularly when I believed then as I do now that I did n't do anything wrong.'' As <ORGANIZATION> IBC </ORGANIZATION> has grown from two employees in 1982 to 2,000 employees this year, the demands on Scallen have increased. But he says he loves it and he has refused to dilute his control over the company. `` This company is my life and it's a delight,'' <PERSON> Scallen </PERSON> said from his top-floor office in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>' signature skyscraper, the IDS Center. Splitting time between <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> and an office in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Scallen </PERSON> operates the company with a skeletal administration that includes no middle managers. He says he wo n't make an acquisition `` unless it's a business I can run myself,'' and he still spends time at the ice rink staging Ice Capades shows. `` That's how I get my kicks,'' <PERSON> Scallen </PERSON> said. `` Those shows are the last big spectaculars in this country.'' <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Follese </PERSON>, who follows <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Summit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, said her only concern about the company is that <PERSON> Scallen </PERSON> tries to do everything. `` When I started with this stock it was a dime,'' <PERSON> Follese </PERSON> said. `` I just thought <PERSON> Scallen </PERSON> was going to do it and sure enough he did. He's performed some real nice miracles lately.''
