 The stock market posted a tiny gain today, but the pace of trading was sluggish. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which fell 17.07 points on Monday, was up 1.78 points to 2,082.86 as of noontime. Advancing issues held a slim lead over declines on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, with 633 up, 610 down and 529 unchanged. <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> volume totaled 70.58 million shares at noon on Wall Street, compared with 69.80 million shares at the same point on Monday. `` It's been pretty dull,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Jensen </PERSON>, a technical market analyst for the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> MKI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` People are waiting for something more conclusive to stir them off the sidelines,'' he said. The government's downward revision of its estimate of second-quarter economic growth failed to provide any stimulus to traders. <PERSON> Jensen </PERSON> noted that the report had virtually no impact on bond prices, which often rally on indications of moderating economic growth. At midday, <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> notes and bond prices were trading close to Monday's late levels. With bond yields still relatively attractive, <PERSON> Jensen </PERSON> said many traders have found incentive to take the risks associated with the uncertain returns on stocks. Among the blue chip issues, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> was up -LRB- at 26 -RRB-, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> was unchanged at 45 and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> fell -LCB- to 28 -LCB-. <ORGANIZATION> Kr