<HEAD>London Stocks Advance 12.2 Points</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with close.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices finished higher in calm trading Tuesday, supported by news of slower-than-expected growth in British bank lending during August. Although prices on Wall Street were retreating by the close of the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> session, British equities stood their ground and barely budged from their session peaks. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index closed 12.2 points, or 0.7 percent, higher at 1,772.1, just below its best level for the day of 1,772.8. Volume remained light, with 309.2 million shares changing hands, compared with 326.7 million shares traded Monday. The British bank lending figures helped ease concern that <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s interest rates might have to move higher over the short term in response to nagging inflationary pressures. The report showed that the most widely watched indication of domestic bank lending rose 5.8 billion pounds, the equivalent of $ 9.7 billion, in August, less than July's 9.2 billion-pound rise, and less than the 7 billion-pound to 10 billion-pound rise expected by the market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
