<HEAD>Securities Exec: Reasons To Support Farmer Mac Despite Unknowns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN P. ROSENFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Unless the financial industry takes a real interest in a new form of farm lending, the opportunity may not arise again, an investment firm executive told a forum of Midwestern bankers Tuesday. <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodman </PERSON> said the newly created <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, known as <ORGANIZATION> Farmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION>, could help banks keep rural customers and reduce the risk of writing farm loans. Farmers, meantime, are hoping the agency will spur competition for farm loans and hold down interest rates. <PERSON> Rodman </PERSON> said that despite high hopes for Farmer Mac, there are many unanswered questions about the agency designed to establish a secondary market for farm loans. One big unknown is how much of a demand exists for such new markets. If Farmer Mac does not sell well, `` I'm afraid it's an opportunity we may not get again,'' he told a seminar at the <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> convention. Farmer Mac was established by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to enable rural lenders such as banks, insurance companies and the Farm Credit System to combine loans and use those pools of mortgages as security for investments sold to the public. It is still in the process of being organized and is months away from adopting even such basic regulations as how its loan pools will be organized. <PERSON> Rodman </PERSON> is vice president for marketing for <ORGANIZATION> MABSCO </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines-based </LOCATION> company designed to provide banks access to secondary markets. <ORGANIZATION> MABSCO </ORGANIZATION> is owned by the insurance company <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> and state banking associations in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and 11 other states. <PERSON> Rodman </PERSON> said his company is interested in becoming one of the organizations pooling farm loans and selling mortgage-backed securities to investors. About $ 8 billion in new farm mortgage credit is extended every year, and only part of that will qualify for <ORGANIZATION> Farmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION> securities, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION>. That will make Farmer Mac a small country cousin to such providers of secondary residential mortgages as <ORGANIZATION> Ginnie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mae </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Freddie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Fannie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mae </ORGANIZATION>. The outstanding principal balances of residential mortgages backing securities guaranteed by those three established agencies, formally known as the <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, totaled more than $ 670 billion at the end of last year, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>. What's more, farm loan demand has been in the doldrums in recent months. Following the farm crisis of the first half of the 1980s, in which farm debt rose to record levels, bringing down many banks, survivors began staging a recovery assisted by huge government subsidies. As a result, many surviving agricultural and rural banks are flush with cash. But <PERSON> Rodman </PERSON> said credit could begin getting tight as early as 1989 making <ORGANIZATION> Farmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION> a welcome tool for assuring liquidity and enabling lenders to shift the risk of long-term loans to investors. This summer's drought reduced crop yields, thinned livestock herds and held down many farmers' income at a time when the government is beginning to move to reduce its subsidies, and analysts are predicting loan demand from farmers will be growing as they expand plantings next spring. Not only are farmers expected to plant more next year, but the price of seed and fertilizer is rising and interest rates have been headed higher. `` If loan funds get tight, we can see demand develop quickly'' to harness <ORGANIZATION> Farmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Rodman </PERSON> said. Analysts say yields on Farmer Mac securities should be competitive with <ORGANIZATION> Fannie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mae </ORGANIZATION> and other secondary markets for mortgages. The securities will be backed with a $ 1.5 billion line of credit at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Treasury that can be tapped if losses in any mortgage pool exceed a 10 percent reserve fund established by lenders and pool operators.
</TEXT>
