<HEAD>Dollar Closes Lower; Gold Rises Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar drifted lower against most major foreign currencies in light European trading Tuesday, reflecting more reluctance by dealers to do business ahead of top-level finance minister meetings this week. Gold prices rose slightly in quiet trading. Markets ignored a downward revision in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> gross national product figures for the second quarter to 3.0 percent from 3.3 percent, foreign currency dealers said. They were more concerned with the potential impact of meetings starting Thursday by the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> IMF-World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> discussions on international debt will be followed by a Saturday gathering of finance ministers from the leading industrialized democracies. Both meetings will be held in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. Ministers from the so-called <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seven </ORGANIZATION> countries _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> _ are expected to push for stable currency exchange rates, dealers said. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends as <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar edged up 0.35 Japanese yen to a closing 134.15 yen. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> it retreated to 133.90 yen. Many dealers said the worsening health of Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> and a second-quarter decline of 1.0 percent in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s gross national product pushed the yen down. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost $ 1.6865 to buy one pound, more expensive than its $ 1.6785 level late Monday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> compared with late Monday: 1.8641 West German marks, down from 1.8695; 1.5740 Swiss francs, down from 1.5793; 6.3385 French francs, down from 6.3520; 2.1075 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1100; 1,391.50 Italian lire, down from 1,393.50; 1.2203 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2194. Higher gold prices reflected internal market influences rather than renewed interest in the metal, said one <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> bullion dealer. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, gold edged up to $ 410 a troy ounce from late Monday's $ 409.30 In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold closed at $ 410.50, up from $ 408.50 late Monday. Earlier in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> gold rose $ 1.72 to close at $ 413.12. Silver bullion prices rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to $ 6.36 a troy ounce, from Monday's $ 6.28.
</TEXT>
