<HEAD>Pillsbury First-Quarter Income Up 26 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday its first-quarter earnings rose 26 percent, in part because of a change in accounting for income taxes. <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> said it earned $ 71.4 million, or 83 cents per share, during the quarter ended Aug. 31, compared with $ 56.8 million, or 66 cents per share, in the same period a year ago. The company noted in a statement that its income was boosted $ 14 million as a result of the recalculation of prior years' deferred income taxes. Sales rose 2 percent to $ 1.48 billion from $ 1.46 billion. `` This represents the first step toward a better year in fiscal 1989, a year in which we expect to gain momentum toward much better long-term prospects,'' said <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman, president and chief executive officer. <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s food business has shown improvement, but the company is still spending heavily to boost its slumping restaurants division, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. The restaurants unit reported a 34 percent decline in operating profit to $ 48.7 million from $ 73.5 million as sales declined 7 percent to $ 655 million. The unit includes Burger King, Steak and Ale and Godfather's Pizza. On Monday, <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> announced it was selling Godfather's to the chain's management for an undisclosed amount.
