<HEAD>Stocks Tumble, Dollar Higher In Tokyo Morning Session</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei, comments. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices fell sharply after a slight rebound in morning trading Wednesday, while the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar inched up against the Japanese yen. The <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, a 352.42-point loser Tuesday, closed the morning session down another 253.02 points at 27,295.56, after rising slightly in the minutes of trading. `` Share prices were lower across the board, even print-related issues declined,'' a <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>' analyst said. `` Participants just did n't know what to do because they were worried about what would happen to the stock market in case the emperor died. So most of them were trying to get rid of the issues they were unsure of in the future,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity. The <ORGANIZATION> Imperial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Household </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday morning that Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s condition was improving after three blood transfusions and other treatment Tuesday. News reports said he has been in serious condition since vomiting blood Monday night and early Tuesday morning. The analyst also said investors were pessimistic over the decline in the growth rate of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s gross national product for the second quarter, which was reported Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s gross national product for the April-June period was 3.9 percent, down 0.1 percent from the previous quarter. According to the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> report, it was the first decline after increases in the last nine quarters. In foreign exchange, the dollar was quoted at 134.18 yen by late morning, up from 134.15 yen at Tuesday's close and from 134.05 yen at the opening of trading.
